{"title_page": "The Tell-Tale Heart", "text_new": "{{short description|Short story by Edgar Allan Poe}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name              = The Tell-Tale Heart\n| image             = The Pioneer Poe 1843 cover 2.jpg\n| image_size        = 200px\n| caption           = ''The Pioneer'', Vol. I, No. I, Drew and Scammell, Philadelphia, January, 1843\n| title_orig        =\n| translator        =\n| author            = [[Edgar Allan Poe]]\n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| series            =\n| genre             = [[Horror fiction|Horror]], [[Gothic Literature]]\n| published_in      = ''The Pioneer''\n| publication_type  = [[Periodical]]\n| publisher         = [[James Russell Lowell]]\n| media_type        = Print ([[periodical]])\n| pub_date          = January 1843\n| english_pub_date  =\n| preceded_by       =\n| followed_by       =\n}}\n\n\"'''The Tell-Tale Heart'''\" is a [[short story]] by American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]], first published in 1843. It is related by an unnamed narrator who endeavors to convince the reader of the narrator\u2019s sanity while simultaneously describing a murder the narrator committed. The victim was an old man with a filmy \"vulture-eye\", as the narrator calls it. The narrator emphasizes the careful calculation of the murder, attempting the perfect crime, complete with dismembering and hiding the body under the floorboards. Ultimately, the narrator's feelings of guilt, or a mental disturbance, result in hearing a thumping sound, which the narrator interprets as the dead man's beating heart.\n\nThe story was first published in [[James Russell Lowell]]'s ''The Pioneer'' in January 1843. \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is often considered a classic of the [[Gothic fiction]] genre and is one of Poe's best known short stories.\n\nThe specific motivation for murder (aside from the narrator's dislike of the old man's eye), the relationship between narrator and old man, the gender of the narrator and other details are left unclear. The narrator denies having any feelings of hatred or resentment for the man who had, as stated, never wronged the narrator. The narrator also denies having killed for greed. \n\nIt has been speculated that the old man is a father figure, the narrator's landlord, or that the narrator works for the old man as a servant, and that perhaps his \"vulture-eye\" represents some sort of veiled secret, or power. The ambiguity and lack of details about the two main characters stand in stark contrast to the specific plot details leading up to the murder.\n\n==Plot summary==\n[[File:Clarke-TellTaleHeart.jpeg|thumb|left|Illustration by [[Harry Clarke]], 1919]]\n\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is told from a [[first-person narrative]] of an unnamed narrator, who insists on being sane, but is suffering from a disease (nervousness) which causes \"[[Hyperesthesia|over-acuteness of the senses]]\". \n\nThe old man with whom the narrator lives has a clouded, pale, blue \"[[vulture]]-like\" eye, which distresses the narrator so much that the narrator plots to murder the old man, despite also insisting that the narrator loves the old man. The narrator insists that this careful precision in committing the murder proves that the narrator cannot possibly be insane. For seven nights, the narrator opens the door of the old man's room in order to shine a sliver of light onto the \"evil eye\". However, the old man's vulture-eye is always closed, making it impossible to \"do the work\".\n\nOn the eighth night, the old man awakens after the narrator's hand slips and makes a noise, interrupting the narrator's nightly ritual. But the narrator does not draw back and, after some time, decides to open the lantern. A single thin ray of light shines out and lands precisely on the \"evil eye\", revealing that it is wide open. Hearing the old man's heart beating loudly and dangerously fast from terror, the narrator decides to strike, jumping out with a loud yell and smothering the old man with his own bed. The narrator then dismembers the body and conceals the pieces under the floorboards, and ensures the concealment of all signs of the crime. Even so, the old man's scream during the night causes a neighbor to report to the police, who the narrator invites in to look around. The narrator claims that the scream heard was the narrator's own in a nightmare and that the man is absent in the country. Confident that they will not find any evidence of the murder, the narrator brings chairs for them and they sit in the old man's room, on the very spot where the body is concealed, and suspect nothing, as the narrator has a pleasant and easy manner.\n\nThe narrator begins to feel uncomfortable and notices a ringing in the narrator's ears. As the ringing grows louder, the narrator comes to the conclusion that it is the heartbeat of the old man coming from under the floorboards. The sound increases steadily, though the officers seem to pay no attention to it. Terrified by the violent beating of the heart, and convinced that the officers are aware not only of the heartbeat but also of the narrator's guilt, the narrator breaks down and confesses, telling them to tear up the floorboards to reveal the remains of the old man's body.\n\n== Publication history ==\n[[File:Tell tale heart in pioneer.jpg|thumb|\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" in ''The Pioneer: A Literary and Critical Magazine'', page 29]]\n\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was first published in January 1843 in the inaugural issue of ''The Pioneer: A Literary and Critical Magazine'', a short-lived [[Boston]] magazine edited by [[James Russell Lowell]] and [[Robert Carter (editor)|Robert Carter]] who were listed as the \"proprietors\" on the front cover. The magazine was published in Boston by Leland and Whiting and in Philadelphia by Drew and Scammell.\n\nPoe was likely paid $10 for the story.<ref name=\"Silverman-p201\">Silverman, Kenneth. ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-ending Remembrance''. New York: Harper Perennial, 1991. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}, p. 201.</ref> Its original publication included an epigraph which quoted [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]]'s poem \"[[A Psalm of Life]]\".<ref name=Moss151>Moss, Sidney P. ''Poe's Literary Battles: The Critic in the Context of His Literary Milieu''. Southern Illinois University Press, 1969. p. 151</ref> The story was slightly revised when republished in the August 23, 1845, edition of the ''[[Broadway Journal]]''. This edition omitted Longfellow's poem because Poe believed it was plagiarized.<ref name=Moss151/> \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was reprinted several additional times during Poe's lifetime.<ref name=\"eapoe\">{{cite web | date = September 30, 2007 | url = http://www.eapoe.org/works/tales/index.htm | title = \"The Tales of Edgar Allan Poe\" (index) | work = eapoe.org | publisher = The Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore | accessdate = 2007-11-05}}</ref>\n\n== Analysis ==\n\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" uses an [[unreliable narrator]]. The exactness with which the narrator recounts murdering the old man, as if the stealthy way in which they executed the crime were evidence of their sanity, reveals their [[monomania]] and [[paranoia]]. The focus of the story is the perverse scheme to commit the [[perfect crime]].<ref>Kennedy, J. Gerald. ''Poe, Death, and the Life of Writing''. Yale University Press, 1987. p. 132; {{ISBN|0-300-03773-2}}</ref>\n\nThe narrator of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is generally assumed to be a male. However, some critics have suggested a woman may be narrating; no pronouns are used to clarify one way or the other.<ref name=Sova234>Sova, Dawn B. ''Edgar Allan Poe: A to Z''. New York City: Checkmark Books, 2001: 234. {{ISBN|0-8160-4161-X}}</ref> The story starts ''[[in medias res]]''. The story opens with a conversation already in progress between the narrator and another person who is not identified in any way. It has been speculated that the narrator is confessing to a prison warden, a judge, a reporter, a doctor or ([[Anachronism|anachronistically]]) a psychiatrist.<ref name=\"Benfey-p30\">[[Christopher Benfey|Benfey, Christopher]]. \"Poe and the Unreadable: 'The Black Cat' and 'The Tell-Tale Heart'\", in ''New Essays on Poe's Major Tales'', Kenneth Silverman, ed. Cambridge University Press, 1993. {{ISBN|978-0-521-42243-7}}, p. 30.</ref> In any case, the narrator tells the story in great detail.<ref name=\"Cleman-p70\">Cleman, John. \"Irresistible Impulses: Edgar Allan Poe and the Insanity Defense\", in ''Bloom's BioCritiques: Edgar Allan Poe'', edited by Harold Bloom. Philadelphia: Chelsea House Publishers, 2002. {{ISBN|0-7910-6173-6}}, p. 70.</ref> What follows is a study of terror but, more specifically, the memory of terror, as the narrator is relating events from the past.<ref>Quinn, Arthur Hobson. ''Edgar Allan Poe: A Critical Biography''. Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8018-5730-9}}. p. 394</ref> The first word of the story, \"True!\", is an admission of their guilt, as well as an assurance of reliability.<ref name=\"Benfey-p30\"/> This introduction also serves to gain the reader's attention.<ref>Meyers, Jeffrey. ''Edgar Allan Poe: His Life and Legacy''. Cooper Square Press, 1992. p. 101. {{ISBN|0-8154-1038-7}}</ref> Every word contributes to the purpose of moving the story forward, exemplifying Poe's theories about the writing of short stories.<ref>Quinn, Arthur Hobson. ''Edgar Allan Poe: A Critical Biography''. Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1998. p. 394. {{ISBN|0-8018-5730-9}}</ref>\n\nThe story is driven not by the narrator's insistence upon their \"innocence\", but by their insistence on their sanity. This, however, is self-destructive, because in attempting to prove their sanity, they fully admit that they are guilty of murder.<ref name=\"Robinson-p94\">Robinson, E. Arthur. \"Poe's 'The Tell-Tale Heart'\" in ''Twentieth Century Interpretations of Poe's Tales'', edited by William L. Howarth. Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Prentice-Hall Inc., 1971, p. 94.</ref> Their denial of insanity is based on their systematic actions and their precision, as they provide a rational explanation for irrational behavior.<ref name=\"Cleman-p70\"/> This rationality, however, is undermined by their lack of motive (\"Object there was none. Passion there was none.\"). Despite this, they say, the idea of murder \"haunted me day and night.\"<ref name=\"Robinson-p94\"/>\n\nThe story's final scene shows the result of the narrator's feelings of [[guilt (emotion)|guilt]]. Like many characters in [[Gothic fiction]], they allow their nerves to dictate their nature. Despite their best efforts at defending themself, their \"over-acuteness of the senses\", which help them hear the heart beating beneath the floorboards, is evidence that they are truly mad.<ref name=\"Fisher-p87\">Fisher, Benjamin Franklin. \"Poe and the Gothic Tradition\", in ''The Cambridge Companion to Edgar Allan Poe'', edited by Kevin J. Hayes. Cambridge University Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-521-79727-6}}, p. 87.</ref> Poe's contemporaries may well have been reminded of the controversy over the [[insanity defense]] in the 1840s.<ref name=\"Cleman-p66\">Cleman, ''Bloom's BioCritiques'', p. 66.</ref>\n\nThe narrator claims to have a disease that causes [[Sensitivity (human)|hypersensitivity]]. A similar [[motif (narrative)|motif]] is used for Roderick Usher in \"[[The Fall of the House of Usher]]\" (1839) and in \"The Colloquy of Monos and Una\" (1841).<ref name=\"Reilly\"/> It is unclear, however, if the narrator actually has very [[:wikt:acute|acute]] senses, or if they are merely imagining things. If their condition is believed to be true, what they hear at the end of the story may not be the old man's heart, but [[deathwatch beetle]]s. The narrator first admits to hearing beetles in the wall after startling the old man from his sleep. According to superstition, deathwatch beetles are a sign of impending death. One variety of deathwatch beetle raps its head against surfaces, presumably as part of a mating ritual, while others emit ticking sounds.<ref name=\"Reilly\">Reilly, John E. \"[http://www.eapoe.org/papers/misc1990/jer19691.htm The Lesser Death-Watch and \"'The Tell-Tale Heart'] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218172125/http://www.eapoe.org/papers/misc1990/jer19691.htm |date=December 18, 2009 }}\", in ''The American Transcendental Quarterly''. Second quarter, 1969.</ref> [[Henry David Thoreau]] observed in an 1838 article that deathwatch beetles make sounds similar to a heartbeat.<ref>Robison, E. Arthur. \"[http://www.eapoe.org/pstudies/ps1970/p1971105.htm Thoreau and the Deathwatch in Poe's 'The Tell-Tale Heart']\", in ''Poe Studies'', vol. IV, no. 1. June 1971. pp. 14-16</ref> The beating could even be the sound of the narrator's own heart. Alternatively, if the beating is really a product of the narrator's imagination, it is that uncontrolled imagination that leads to their own destruction.<ref name=\"Eddings-p213\">Eddings, Dennis W. \"Theme and Parody in 'The Raven'\", in ''Poe and His Times: The Artist and His Milieu'', edited by Benjamin Franklin Fisher IV. Baltimore: The Edgar Allan Poe Society, 1990. {{ISBN|0-9616449-2-3}}, p. 213.</ref>\n\nIt is also possible that the narrator has [[paranoid schizophrenia]]. Paranoid schizophrenics very often experience auditory hallucinations. These auditory hallucinations are more often voices, but can also be sounds.<ref name=\"Zimmerman-p39-48\">ZIMMERMAN, BRETT. \u201c\u2018Moral Insanity\u2019 or Paranoid Schizophrenia: Poe's \u2018The Tell-Tale Heart.\u2019\u201d Mosaic: A Journal for the Interdisciplinary Study of Literature, vol. 25, no. 2, 1992, pp. 39\u201348. JSTOR, JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/24780617.</ref> This is of course a very modern view of the work; in Poe's era there was no such diagnosis, and Poe would not have been familiar with a set of symptoms as pertaining to any definite mental disease. \n\nThe relationship between the old man and the narrator is ambiguous. Their names, occupations, and places of residence are not given, contrasting with the strict attention to detail in the plot.<ref name=\"Benfey-p32\">Benfey, ''New Essays'', p. 32.</ref> The narrator may be a servant of the old man's or, as is more often assumed, his child. In that case, the \"vulture-eye\" of the old man as a father figure may symbolize parental surveillance, or the paternal principles of right and wrong. The murder of the eye, then, is a removal of conscience.<ref name=\"Hoffman-p223\">Hoffman, Daniel. ''Poe Poe Poe Poe Poe Poe Poe''. Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press, 1972. {{ISBN|0-8071-2321-8}}, p. 223.</ref> The eye may also represent secrecy: only when the eye is found open on the final night, penetrating the veil of secrecy, is the murder carried out.<ref name=\"Benfey-p33\">Benfey, ''New Essays'', p. 33.</ref>\n\n[[Richard Wilbur]] suggested that the tale is an allegorical representation of Poe's poem \"[[To Science]]\", which depicts a struggle between imagination and science. In \"The Tell-Tale Heart\", the old man may thus represent the scientific and rational mind, while the narrator may stand for the imaginative.<ref name=\"Benfey-pp31-32\">Benfey, ''New Essays'', pp. 31-32.</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n{{Unreliable sources|section|date=January 2016}}\n* The earliest acknowledged adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was in a 1928 20-minute American silent film of that title<ref name=\"Tome332\">{{cite book|last=Workman|first=Christopher|last2=Howarth|first2=Troy|year=2016|title=Tome of Terror: Horror Films of the Silent Era|publisher=Midnight Marquee Press|page=332|ISBN=978-1936168-68-2}}</ref> co-directed by [[Leon Shamroy]] and Charles Klein, and starring [[Otto Matieson]] as \"The Insane\", William Herford as \"The Old Man\" with Charles Darvas and Hans Fuerberg as \"Detectives\". It was faithful to the original tale,<ref name=Sova234/> unlike future television and film adaptations which often expanded the short story to full-length feature films.<ref name=\"imdb-search\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/find?s=tt&q=The+Tell-Tale+Heart|title=IMDb Title Search: The Tell-Tale Heart|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=2007-09-01}}{{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* The earliest known \"talkie\" adaptation was a [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1934 film)|1934 version]] filmed at the Blattner Studios, [[Elstree Studios|Elstree]], by Clifton-Hurst Productions, directed by [[Brian Desmond Hurst]] and starring Norman Dryden. This version was 55 minutes in length.<ref name=\"imdb_0149973\">{{IMDb title|id=0149973|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1934)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* A [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1941 film)|1941 live-action adaptation]] starred [[Joseph Schildkraut]] and was the directorial debut of [[Jules Dassin]].<ref name=\"imdb_0122748\">{{IMDb title|id=0122748|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1941)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>  This version differs greatly from the original tale, depicting the murderer as driven mad after suffering years of abuse by the hateful older man.\n* A [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1953 American film)|1953 animated short film]] produced by [[United Productions of America]] and narrated by [[James Mason]]<ref name=\"imdb_0046408\">{{IMDb title| id = 0046408 | title = The Tell-Tale Heart (1953/I)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref> is included among the [[National Film Registry|list of films preserved in the United States National Film Registry]].\n* Also in 1953, an [[EC Comics]] adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" entitled \"Sleep No More\", written by [[William Gaines]] and [[Al Feldstein]] and illustrated by [[George Evans (cartoonist)]] appeared in ''[[Shock SuspenStories]]''.<ref>\"Sleep No More\", by Bill Gaines and Ed Feldstein, ''Shock SuspenStories'', April 1953.</ref>\n* In 1956, an adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was written by [[William Templeton (screenwriter)|William Templeton]] for the ''[[NBC Matinee Theater]]'' and aired on the 6th November 1956.\n* A 1960 film adaptation, ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1960 film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]],'' adds a love triangle to the story.<ref name=\"imdb_0056565\">{{IMDb title|id=0056565|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1960) }}.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* An [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1961 film)|Australian ballet was based on the story]], and was recorded for television in the early 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oZ5VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gbIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5089%2C2275271 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-05-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518204856/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oZ5VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gbIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5089,2275271 |archive-date=2016-05-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 1970, Vincent Price included a solo recitation of the story in the anthology film ''[[An Evening of Edgar Allan Poe]]''.\n* A 1971 film adaptation directed by Steve Carver, and starring [[Sam Jaffe]] as the old man.<ref name=\"imdb_0260421\">{{IMDb title|id=0260421|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1971)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[CBS Radio Mystery Theater]] performed an adaptation of the story in 1975; the cast included [[Fred Gwynne]].\n* The [[Canada|Canadian]] radio program ''[[Nightfall (CBC)|Nightfall]]'' presented an adaptation on August 1, 1980.\n* A musical adaptation performed by [[The Alan Parsons Project]] was released on their 1976 debut album ''[[Tales of Mystery and Imagination (Alan Parsons Project album)|Tales of Mystery and Imagination]]'', and was later covered by [[Slough Feg]] for their 2010 album, [[The Animal Spirits]].\n*''The Simpsons'' episode \"Lisa's Rival\" is loosely based on the story, wherein Lisa replaces Allison's diorama of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" with a diorama of a cow's heart. Lisa can hear the original diorama operating a heartbeat noise, much like in the story.\n* During [[Tiny Toon Adventures]] 1995 Halloween special ''Night Ghoulery''<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiny Toons' Night Ghoulery|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0123298/|work=The Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> the story was parodied as ''The Tell-Tale Vacuum''\n* A musical adaptation by the [[Insane Clown Posse]] was included on their 1995 album ''The Riddle Box'', entitled \"Ol' Evil Eye\", which covers the story of a young man determined to kill \"old man Willie on the hilltop\" because of his grotesque left eye, and is interspersed with samples from an audio recording of a reading of the original short story.\n* Steven Berkoff adapted the story in 1991, and was broadcast on British television. This adaptation was originally presented on British TV as part of the acclaimed series \"Without Walls\". This version was later broadcast in the United States on the cable channel [[Bravo (US TV channel)|BRAVO]] as part of the ''[[Texaco]] Performing Arts'' series.\n* The Christian Thrash / Hybrid Metal band Tourniquet adapted the story into song for their 1997 release \"Crawl To China\". A hidden bonus track on the album captures an adaptation of the conversation between the main character and the police officers without music. Drummer/primary songwriter Ted Kirkpatrick is a huge fan of Edgar Alan Poe and has also released an album of poems and songs featuring adaptations of his works. \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is the opening track, and is read by Les Carlson (vocalist for the Metal band Bloodgood). \n* The [[Radio Tales]] series produced ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (radio)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]'' for [[National Public Radio]] in 1998. The story was performed by [[Winifred Phillips]] along with music composed by her.\n* The [[PB&J Otter]] episode \u201cThe Tell-Tale Candy Wrapper,\u201d first aired in 1999, is a parody of the story.\n* The ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'' episode \"Squeaky Boots,\" first aired in 1999, is loosely based on the story.<ref>{{Citation|last=Kenny|first=Tom|title=Sandy's Rocket/Squeaky Boots|date=1999-09-04|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0769436/trivia|last2=Bumpass|last3=Fagerbakke|last4=Brown|first2=Rodger|first3=Bill|first4=Clancy|accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref> \n* [[Tom Smith (filker)|Tom Smith]] released \"Telly Taley Heart\" in 1999, recounting the story to the tune of \"[[Achy Breaky Heart]]\".\n* A musical adaptation, entitled \"Dark Chilling Heartbeat\", was performed by [[Deceased (band)|Deceased]] on their 2000 album ''[[Supernatural Addiction]]''.\n* The film ''Nightmares from the Mind of Poe'' (2006) adapts \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" along with \"[[The Cask of Amontillado]]\", \"[[The Premature Burial]]\" and \"[[The Raven]]\".\n* The 2009 thriller film ''[[Tell-Tale (film)|Tell-Tale]]'', produced by [[Ridley Scott]] and [[Tony Scott]], credits Poe's \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" as the basis for the story of a man being haunted by his donor's memories, after a heart transplant.<ref name=\"imdb_1135095\">{{IMDb title|id=1135095|title=Tell-Tale (2009)}}</ref>{{unreliable<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malvern |first1=Jack |title=Edgar Allen Poe\u2019s horror classic The Tell\u2011Tale Heart back from the dead after attic clear\u2011out |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/edgar-allen-poe-s-horror-classic-the-tell-tale-heart-back-from-the-dead-after-attic-clear-out-8bz8jdljs |accessdate=30 November 2018 |work=[[The Times]] |date=23 October 2018}}</ref> source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* V. H. Belvadi's 2012 short film, ''Telltale'', credits Poe's \"The Tell-tale Heart\" as its inspiration and uses some dialog from the original work.<ref name=\"imdb_2339066\">{{IMDb title| id = 2339066 | title = Telltale (2012) }}.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* A 2013 Spanish short film adaptation, ''Entra\u00f1as'' (\"Entrails\"), was directed by Narciso Velver.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3264020/|title=Entra\u00f1as (2013)|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Movie Database|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Poe's Tell-Tale Heart: The Game'', is a 2013 mobile game adaptation in which players enact the protagonist's actions to recreate Poe's story on Google Play<ref>{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.learnvideogames.poe&hl=en |title=Poe's Tell-Tale Heart:The Game - Android Apps on Google Play |website=Play.google.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> and Apple iOS.\n* The 2015 animated anthology ''Extraordinary Tales'' includes \"The Tell-Tale Heart\", narrated by [[Bela Lugosi]].\n* The 2015 [[Lifetime movie]] ''The Murder Pact'', starring [[Alexa Vega]], is based on Poe's work and incorporates allusions to it, such as the \"vulture eye\" from \"The Tell-Tale Heart\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Traciy Reyes |url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2411726/the-murder-pact-lifetime-movie-tell-tale-lies-lindsey-stirling-music-trailer-not-true-story/ |title=\u2018The Murder Pact\u2019: Lifetime Movie, Also Known As \u2018Tell-Tale Lies\u2019, Airs Tonight Featuring Music By Lindsey Stirling |website=Inquisitr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* In April 2016, a film adaption directed by John Le Tier was released, entitled \"The Tell-Tale Heart\". It starred Peter Bogdonavich, Rose McGowan, and Patrick John Flueger in the lead role. It featured a full narration of Poe's story with added elements imagining the narrator as a former tortured soldier with PTSD.\n* In spring 2017, [[Udon Entertainment]]'s Manga Classics line will publish ''The Stories of Edgar Allan Poe'', which will include a manga format adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\".<ref>[http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-07-21/udon-ent-to-release-street-fighter-novel-dragon-crown-manga/.104545 \"Udon Ent. to Release Street Fighter Novel, Dragon's Crown Manga\"], Anime News Network, July 21, 2016</ref>\n* In December 2018, [[Anthony Neilson]]'s stage adaptation was presented at London's [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malvern |first1=Jack |title=Edgar Allen Poe\u2019s horror classic The Tell\u2011Tale Heart back from the dead after attic clear\u2011out |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/edgar-allen-poe-s-horror-classic-the-tell-tale-heart-back-from-the-dead-after-attic-clear-out-8bz8jdljs |work=[[The Times]] |date=23 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* The language-learning service [[Duolingo]]\u2019s website features a six-part version of Poe\u2019s story in Spanish, dramatically narrated and with interactive prompts for learners to use to test their Spanish knowledge.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|Mystery Tales of Edgar Allan Poe/The Tell-Tale Heart|The Tell-Tale Heart}}\n{{Commonscat}}\n* [https://www.poemuseum.org/works-telltale.php \"The Poe Museum\"] - Full text of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\"\n* [http://www.eapoe.org/works/tales/thearta.htm \"The Tell-Tale Heart\"] - Full text of the first printing, from the ''Pioneer'', 1843\n* [http://www.escape-suspense.com/2007/10/the-tell-tale-h.html Mid-20th century radio adaptations of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\"]\n* [http://www.shmoop.com/tell-tale-heart/ \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" study guide and teaching guide] - themes, analysis, quotes, teacher resources\n* [http://www.TheTell-TaleHeart.com \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" animation] - Award-winning 2010 animated movie, teacher resources, student games\n* [https://librivox.org/search?q=The%20Tell-Tale%20Heart&search_form=advanced 20 LibriVox audiorecordings, read by various readers]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/pioneerliteraryc01lowe#page/n5/mode/2up The Pioneer, January, 1843, Boston edition.]\n{{Edgar Allan Poe}}\n{{The Tell-Tale Heart}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tell-Tale Heart, The}}\n[[Category:1843 short stories]]\n[[Category:Horror short stories]]\n[[Category:Fiction with unreliable narrators]]\n[[Category:Short stories adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Edgar Allan Poe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Short story by Edgar Allan Poe}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox short story | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name              = The Tell-Tale Heart\n| image             = The Pioneer Poe 1843 cover 2.jpg\n| image_size        = 200px\n| caption           = ''The Pioneer'', Vol. I, No. I, Drew and Scammell, Philadelphia, January, 1843\n| title_orig        =\n| translator        =\n| author            = [[Edgar Allan Poe]]\n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| series            =\n| genre             = [[Horror fiction|Horror]], [[Gothic Literature]]\n| published_in      = ''The Pioneer''\n| publication_type  = [[Periodical]]\n| publisher         = [[James Russell Lowell]]\n| media_type        = Print ([[periodical]])\n| pub_date          = January 1843\n| english_pub_date  =\n| preceded_by       =\n| followed_by       =\n}}\n\n\"'''The Tell-Tale Heart'''\" is a [[short story]] by American writer [[Edgar Allan Poe]], first published in 1843. It is related by an unnamed narrator who endeavors to convince the reader of the narrator\u2019s sanity while simultaneously describing a murder the narrator committed. The victim was an old man with a filmy \"vulture-eye\", as the narrator calls it. The narrator emphasizes the careful calculation of the murder, attempting the perfect crime, complete with dismembering and hiding the body under the floorboards. Ultimately, the narrator's feelings of guilt, or a mental disturbance, result in hearing a thumping sound, which the narrator interprets as the dead man's beating heart.\n\nThe story was first published in [[James Russell Lowell]]'s ''The Pioneer'' in January 1843. \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is often considered a classic of the [[Gothic fiction]] genre and is one of Poe's best known short stories.\n\nThe specific motivation for murder (aside from the narrator's dislike of the old man's eye), the relationship between narrator and old man, the gender of the narrator and other details are left unclear. The narrator denies having any feelings of hatred or resentment for the man who had, as stated, never wronged the narrator. The narrator also denies having killed for greed. \n\nIt has been speculated that the old man is a father figure, the narrator's landlord, or that the narrator works for the old man as a servant, and that perhaps his \"vulture-eye\" represents some sort of veiled secret, or power. The ambiguity and lack of details about the two main characters stand in stark contrast to the specific plot details leading up to the murder.\n\n==Plot summary==\n[[File:Clarke-TellTaleHeart.jpeg|thumb|left|Illustration by [[Harry Clarke]], 1919]]\n\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is a [[first-person narrative]] of an unnamed narrator, who insists on being sane, but is suffering from a disease (nervousness) which causes \"[[Hyperesthesia|over-acuteness of the senses]]\". \n\nThe old man with whom the narrator lives has a clouded, pale, blue \"[[vulture]]-like\" eye, which distresses the narrator so much that the narrator plots to murder the old man, despite also insisting that the narrator loves the old man. The narrator insists that this careful precision in committing the murder proves that the narrator cannot possibly be insane. For seven nights, the narrator opens the door of the old man's room in order to shine a sliver of light onto the \"evil eye\". However, the old man's vulture-eye is always closed, making it impossible to \"do the work\".\n\nOn the eighth night, the old man awakens after the narrator's hand slips and makes a noise, interrupting the narrator's nightly ritual. But the narrator does not draw back and, after some time, decides to open the lantern. A single thin ray of light shines out and lands precisely on the \"evil eye\", revealing that it is wide open. Hearing the old man's heart beating loudly and dangerously fast from terror, the narrator decides to strike, jumping out with a loud yell and smothering the old man with his own bed. The narrator then dismembers the body and conceals the pieces under the floorboards, and ensures the concealment of all signs of the crime. Even so, the old man's scream during the night causes a neighbor to report to the police, who the narrator invites in to look around. The narrator claims that the scream heard was the narrator's own in a nightmare and that the man is absent in the country. Confident that they will not find any evidence of the murder, the narrator brings chairs for them and they sit in the old man's room, on the very spot where the body is concealed, and suspect nothing, as the narrator has a pleasant and easy manner.\n\nThe narrator begins to feel uncomfortable and notices a ringing in the narrator's ears. As the ringing grows louder, the narrator comes to the conclusion that it is the heartbeat of the old man coming from under the floorboards. The sound increases steadily, though the officers seem to pay no attention to it. Terrified by the violent beating of the heart, and convinced that the officers are aware not only of the heartbeat but also of the narrator's guilt, the narrator breaks down and confesses, telling them to tear up the floorboards to reveal the remains of the old man's body.\n\n== Publication history ==\n[[File:Tell tale heart in pioneer.jpg|thumb|\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" in ''The Pioneer: A Literary and Critical Magazine'', page 29]]\n\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was first published in January 1843 in the inaugural issue of ''The Pioneer: A Literary and Critical Magazine'', a short-lived [[Boston]] magazine edited by [[James Russell Lowell]] and [[Robert Carter (editor)|Robert Carter]] who were listed as the \"proprietors\" on the front cover. The magazine was published in Boston by Leland and Whiting and in Philadelphia by Drew and Scammell.\n\nPoe was likely paid $10 for the story.<ref name=\"Silverman-p201\">Silverman, Kenneth. ''Edgar A. Poe: Mournful and Never-ending Remembrance''. New York: Harper Perennial, 1991. {{ISBN|0-06-092331-8}}, p. 201.</ref> Its original publication included an epigraph which quoted [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]]'s poem \"[[A Psalm of Life]]\".<ref name=Moss151>Moss, Sidney P. ''Poe's Literary Battles: The Critic in the Context of His Literary Milieu''. Southern Illinois University Press, 1969. p. 151</ref> The story was slightly revised when republished in the August 23, 1845, edition of the ''[[Broadway Journal]]''. This edition omitted Longfellow's poem because Poe believed it was plagiarized.<ref name=Moss151/> \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was reprinted several additional times during Poe's lifetime.<ref name=\"eapoe\">{{cite web | date = September 30, 2007 | url = http://www.eapoe.org/works/tales/index.htm | title = \"The Tales of Edgar Allan Poe\" (index) | work = eapoe.org | publisher = The Edgar Allan Poe Society of Baltimore | accessdate = 2007-11-05}}</ref>\n\n== Analysis ==\n\"The Tell-Tale Heart\" uses an [[unreliable narrator]]. The exactness with which the narrator recounts murdering the old man, as if the stealthy way in which they executed the crime were evidence of their sanity, reveals their [[monomania]] and [[paranoia]]. The focus of the story is the perverse scheme to commit the [[perfect crime]].<ref>Kennedy, J. Gerald. ''Poe, Death, and the Life of Writing''. Yale University Press, 1987. p. 132; {{ISBN|0-300-03773-2}}</ref>\n\nThe narrator of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is generally assumed to be a male. However, some critics have suggested a woman may be narrating; no pronouns are used to clarify one way or the other.<ref name=Sova234>Sova, Dawn B. ''Edgar Allan Poe: A to Z''. New York City: Checkmark Books, 2001: 234. {{ISBN|0-8160-4161-X}}</ref> The story starts ''[[in medias res]]''. The story opens with a conversation already in progress between the narrator and another person who is not identified in any way. It has been speculated that the narrator is confessing to a prison warden, a judge, a reporter, a doctor or ([[Anachronism|anachronistically]]) a psychiatrist.<ref name=\"Benfey-p30\">[[Christopher Benfey|Benfey, Christopher]]. \"Poe and the Unreadable: 'The Black Cat' and 'The Tell-Tale Heart'\", in ''New Essays on Poe's Major Tales'', Kenneth Silverman, ed. Cambridge University Press, 1993. {{ISBN|978-0-521-42243-7}}, p. 30.</ref> In any case, the narrator tells the story in great detail.<ref name=\"Cleman-p70\">Cleman, John. \"Irresistible Impulses: Edgar Allan Poe and the Insanity Defense\", in ''Bloom's BioCritiques: Edgar Allan Poe'', edited by Harold Bloom. Philadelphia: Chelsea House Publishers, 2002. {{ISBN|0-7910-6173-6}}, p. 70.</ref> What follows is a study of terror but, more specifically, the memory of terror, as the narrator is relating events from the past.<ref>Quinn, Arthur Hobson. ''Edgar Allan Poe: A Critical Biography''. Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8018-5730-9}}. p. 394</ref> The first word of the story, \"True!\", is an admission of their guilt, as well as an assurance of reliability.<ref name=\"Benfey-p30\"/> This introduction also serves to gain the reader's attention.<ref>Meyers, Jeffrey. ''Edgar Allan Poe: His Life and Legacy''. Cooper Square Press, 1992. p. 101. {{ISBN|0-8154-1038-7}}</ref> Every word contributes to the purpose of moving the story forward, exemplifying Poe's theories about the writing of short stories.<ref>Quinn, Arthur Hobson. ''Edgar Allan Poe: A Critical Biography''. Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1998. p. 394. {{ISBN|0-8018-5730-9}}</ref>\n\nThe story is driven not by the narrator's insistence upon their \"innocence\", but by their insistence on their sanity. This, however, is self-destructive, because in attempting to prove their sanity, they fully admit that they are guilty of murder.<ref name=\"Robinson-p94\">Robinson, E. Arthur. \"Poe's 'The Tell-Tale Heart'\" in ''Twentieth Century Interpretations of Poe's Tales'', edited by William L. Howarth. Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Prentice-Hall Inc., 1971, p. 94.</ref> Their denial of insanity is based on their systematic actions and their precision, as they provide a rational explanation for irrational behavior.<ref name=\"Cleman-p70\"/> This rationality, however, is undermined by their lack of motive (\"Object there was none. Passion there was none.\"). Despite this, they say, the idea of murder \"haunted me day and night.\"<ref name=\"Robinson-p94\"/>\n\nThe story's final scene shows the result of the narrator's feelings of [[guilt (emotion)|guilt]]. Like many characters in [[Gothic fiction]], they allow their nerves to dictate their nature. Despite their best efforts at defending themself, their \"over-acuteness of the senses\", which help them hear the heart beating beneath the floorboards, is evidence that they are truly mad.<ref name=\"Fisher-p87\">Fisher, Benjamin Franklin. \"Poe and the Gothic Tradition\", in ''The Cambridge Companion to Edgar Allan Poe'', edited by Kevin J. Hayes. Cambridge University Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-521-79727-6}}, p. 87.</ref> Poe's contemporaries may well have been reminded of the controversy over the [[insanity defense]] in the 1840s.<ref name=\"Cleman-p66\">Cleman, ''Bloom's BioCritiques'', p. 66.</ref>\n\nThe narrator claims to have a disease that causes [[Sensitivity (human)|hypersensitivity]]. A similar [[motif (narrative)|motif]] is used for Roderick Usher in \"[[The Fall of the House of Usher]]\" (1839) and in \"The Colloquy of Monos and Una\" (1841).<ref name=\"Reilly\"/> It is unclear, however, if the narrator actually has very [[:wikt:acute|acute]] senses, or if they are merely imagining things. If their condition is believed to be true, what they hear at the end of the story may not be the old man's heart, but [[deathwatch beetle]]s. The narrator first admits to hearing beetles in the wall after startling the old man from his sleep. According to superstition, deathwatch beetles are a sign of impending death. One variety of deathwatch beetle raps its head against surfaces, presumably as part of a mating ritual, while others emit ticking sounds.<ref name=\"Reilly\">Reilly, John E. \"[http://www.eapoe.org/papers/misc1990/jer19691.htm The Lesser Death-Watch and \"'The Tell-Tale Heart'] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218172125/http://www.eapoe.org/papers/misc1990/jer19691.htm |date=December 18, 2009 }}\", in ''The American Transcendental Quarterly''. Second quarter, 1969.</ref> [[Henry David Thoreau]] observed in an 1838 article that deathwatch beetles make sounds similar to a heartbeat.<ref>Robison, E. Arthur. \"[http://www.eapoe.org/pstudies/ps1970/p1971105.htm Thoreau and the Deathwatch in Poe's 'The Tell-Tale Heart']\", in ''Poe Studies'', vol. IV, no. 1. June 1971. pp. 14-16</ref> The beating could even be the sound of the narrator's own heart. Alternatively, if the beating is really a product of the narrator's imagination, it is that uncontrolled imagination that leads to their own destruction.<ref name=\"Eddings-p213\">Eddings, Dennis W. \"Theme and Parody in 'The Raven'\", in ''Poe and His Times: The Artist and His Milieu'', edited by Benjamin Franklin Fisher IV. Baltimore: The Edgar Allan Poe Society, 1990. {{ISBN|0-9616449-2-3}}, p. 213.</ref>\n\nIt is also possible that the narrator has [[paranoid schizophrenia]]. Paranoid schizophrenics very often experience auditory hallucinations. These auditory hallucinations are more often voices, but can also be sounds.<ref name=\"Zimmerman-p39-48\">ZIMMERMAN, BRETT. \u201c\u2018Moral Insanity\u2019 or Paranoid Schizophrenia: Poe's \u2018The Tell-Tale Heart.\u2019\u201d Mosaic: A Journal for the Interdisciplinary Study of Literature, vol. 25, no. 2, 1992, pp. 39\u201348. JSTOR, JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/24780617.</ref> This is of course a very modern view of the work; in Poe's era there was no such diagnosis, and Poe would not have been familiar with a set of symptoms as pertaining to any definite mental disease. \n\nThe relationship between the old man and the narrator is ambiguous. Their names, occupations, and places of residence are not given, contrasting with the strict attention to detail in the plot.<ref name=\"Benfey-p32\">Benfey, ''New Essays'', p. 32.</ref> The narrator may be a servant of the old man's or, as is more often assumed, his child. In that case, the \"vulture-eye\" of the old man as a father figure may symbolize parental surveillance, or the paternal principles of right and wrong. The murder of the eye, then, is a removal of conscience.<ref name=\"Hoffman-p223\">Hoffman, Daniel. ''Poe Poe Poe Poe Poe Poe Poe''. Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press, 1972. {{ISBN|0-8071-2321-8}}, p. 223.</ref> The eye may also represent secrecy: only when the eye is found open on the final night, penetrating the veil of secrecy, is the murder carried out.<ref name=\"Benfey-p33\">Benfey, ''New Essays'', p. 33.</ref>\n\n[[Richard Wilbur]] suggested that the tale is an allegorical representation of Poe's poem \"[[To Science]]\", which depicts a struggle between imagination and science. In \"The Tell-Tale Heart\", the old man may thus represent the scientific and rational mind, while the narrator may stand for the imaginative.<ref name=\"Benfey-pp31-32\">Benfey, ''New Essays'', pp. 31-32.</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n{{Unreliable sources|section|date=January 2016}}\n* The earliest acknowledged adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was in a 1928 20-minute American silent film of that title<ref name=\"Tome332\">{{cite book|last=Workman|first=Christopher|last2=Howarth|first2=Troy|year=2016|title=Tome of Terror: Horror Films of the Silent Era|publisher=Midnight Marquee Press|page=332|ISBN=978-1936168-68-2}}</ref> co-directed by [[Leon Shamroy]] and Charles Klein, and starring [[Otto Matieson]] as \"The Insane\", William Herford as \"The Old Man\" with Charles Darvas and Hans Fuerberg as \"Detectives\". It was faithful to the original tale,<ref name=Sova234/> unlike future television and film adaptations which often expanded the short story to full-length feature films.<ref name=\"imdb-search\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/find?s=tt&q=The+Tell-Tale+Heart|title=IMDb Title Search: The Tell-Tale Heart|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=2007-09-01}}{{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* The earliest known \"talkie\" adaptation was a [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1934 film)|1934 version]] filmed at the Blattner Studios, [[Elstree Studios|Elstree]], by Clifton-Hurst Productions, directed by [[Brian Desmond Hurst]] and starring Norman Dryden. This version was 55 minutes in length.<ref name=\"imdb_0149973\">{{IMDb title|id=0149973|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1934)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* A [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1941 film)|1941 live-action adaptation]] starred [[Joseph Schildkraut]] and was the directorial debut of [[Jules Dassin]].<ref name=\"imdb_0122748\">{{IMDb title|id=0122748|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1941)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>  This version differs greatly from the original tale, depicting the murderer as driven mad after suffering years of abuse by the hateful older man.\n* A [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1953 American film)|1953 animated short film]] produced by [[United Productions of America]] and narrated by [[James Mason]]<ref name=\"imdb_0046408\">{{IMDb title| id = 0046408 | title = The Tell-Tale Heart (1953/I)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref> is included among the [[National Film Registry|list of films preserved in the United States National Film Registry]].\n* Also in 1953, an [[EC Comics]] adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" entitled \"Sleep No More\", written by [[William Gaines]] and [[Al Feldstein]] and illustrated by [[George Evans (cartoonist)]] appeared in ''[[Shock SuspenStories]]''.<ref>\"Sleep No More\", by Bill Gaines and Ed Feldstein, ''Shock SuspenStories'', April 1953.</ref>\n* In 1956, an adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" was written by [[William Templeton (screenwriter)|William Templeton]] for the ''[[NBC Matinee Theater]]'' and aired on the 6th November 1956.\n* A 1960 film adaptation, ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1960 film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]],'' adds a love triangle to the story.<ref name=\"imdb_0056565\">{{IMDb title|id=0056565|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1960) }}.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* An [[The Tell-Tale Heart (1961 film)|Australian ballet was based on the story]], and was recorded for television in the early 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oZ5VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gbIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5089%2C2275271 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-05-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518204856/https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oZ5VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gbIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5089,2275271 |archive-date=2016-05-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* In 1970, Vincent Price included a solo recitation of the story in the anthology film ''[[An Evening of Edgar Allan Poe]]''.\n* A 1971 film adaptation directed by Steve Carver, and starring [[Sam Jaffe]] as the old man.<ref name=\"imdb_0260421\">{{IMDb title|id=0260421|title=The Tell-Tale Heart (1971)}} {{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[CBS Radio Mystery Theater]] performed an adaptation of the story in 1975; the cast included [[Fred Gwynne]].\n* The [[Canada|Canadian]] radio program ''[[Nightfall (CBC)|Nightfall]]'' presented an adaptation on August 1, 1980.\n* A musical adaptation performed by [[The Alan Parsons Project]] was released on their 1976 debut album ''[[Tales of Mystery and Imagination (Alan Parsons Project album)|Tales of Mystery and Imagination]]'', and was later covered by [[Slough Feg]] for their 2010 album, [[The Animal Spirits]].\n*''The Simpsons'' episode \"Lisa's Rival\" is loosely based on the story, wherein Lisa replaces Allison's diorama of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" with a diorama of a cow's heart. Lisa can hear the original diorama operating a heartbeat noise, much like in the story.\n* During [[Tiny Toon Adventures]] 1995 Halloween special ''Night Ghoulery''<ref>{{cite web|title=Tiny Toons' Night Ghoulery|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0123298/|work=The Internet Movie Database|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=March 22, 2011}}</ref> the story was parodied as ''The Tell-Tale Vacuum''\n* A musical adaptation by the [[Insane Clown Posse]] was included on their 1995 album ''The Riddle Box'', entitled \"Ol' Evil Eye\", which covers the story of a young man determined to kill \"old man Willie on the hilltop\" because of his grotesque left eye, and is interspersed with samples from an audio recording of a reading of the original short story.\n* Steven Berkoff adapted the story in 1991, and was broadcast on British television. This adaptation was originally presented on British TV as part of the acclaimed series \"Without Walls\". This version was later broadcast in the United States on the cable channel [[Bravo (US TV channel)|BRAVO]] as part of the ''[[Texaco]] Performing Arts'' series.\n* The Christian Thrash / Hybrid Metal band Tourniquet adapted the story into song for their 1997 release \"Crawl To China\". A hidden bonus track on the album captures an adaptation of the conversation between the main character and the police officers without music. Drummer/primary songwriter Ted Kirkpatrick is a huge fan of Edgar Alan Poe and has also released an album of poems and songs featuring adaptations of his works. \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" is the opening track, and is read by Les Carlson (vocalist for the Metal band Bloodgood). \n* The [[Radio Tales]] series produced ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (radio)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]'' for [[National Public Radio]] in 1998. The story was performed by [[Winifred Phillips]] along with music composed by her.\n* The [[PB&J Otter]] episode \u201cThe Tell-Tale Candy Wrapper,\u201d first aired in 1999, is a parody of the story.\n* The ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'' episode \"Squeaky Boots,\" first aired in 1999, is loosely based on the story.<ref>{{Citation|last=Kenny|first=Tom|title=Sandy's Rocket/Squeaky Boots|date=1999-09-04|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0769436/trivia|last2=Bumpass|last3=Fagerbakke|last4=Brown|first2=Rodger|first3=Bill|first4=Clancy|accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref> \n* [[Tom Smith (filker)|Tom Smith]] released \"Telly Taley Heart\" in 1999, recounting the story to the tune of \"[[Achy Breaky Heart]]\".\n* A musical adaptation, entitled \"Dark Chilling Heartbeat\", was performed by [[Deceased (band)|Deceased]] on their 2000 album ''[[Supernatural Addiction]]''.\n* The film ''Nightmares from the Mind of Poe'' (2006) adapts \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" along with \"[[The Cask of Amontillado]]\", \"[[The Premature Burial]]\" and \"[[The Raven]]\".\n* The 2009 thriller film ''[[Tell-Tale (film)|Tell-Tale]]'', produced by [[Ridley Scott]] and [[Tony Scott]], credits Poe's \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" as the basis for the story of a man being haunted by his donor's memories, after a heart transplant.<ref name=\"imdb_1135095\">{{IMDb title|id=1135095|title=Tell-Tale (2009)}}</ref>{{unreliable<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malvern |first1=Jack |title=Edgar Allen Poe\u2019s horror classic The Tell\u2011Tale Heart back from the dead after attic clear\u2011out |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/edgar-allen-poe-s-horror-classic-the-tell-tale-heart-back-from-the-dead-after-attic-clear-out-8bz8jdljs |accessdate=30 November 2018 |work=[[The Times]] |date=23 October 2018}}</ref> source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* V. H. Belvadi's 2012 short film, ''Telltale'', credits Poe's \"The Tell-tale Heart\" as its inspiration and uses some dialog from the original work.<ref name=\"imdb_2339066\">{{IMDb title| id = 2339066 | title = Telltale (2012) }}.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n* A 2013 Spanish short film adaptation, ''Entra\u00f1as'' (\"Entrails\"), was directed by Narciso Velver.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3264020/|title=Entra\u00f1as (2013)|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Movie Database|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* ''Poe's Tell-Tale Heart: The Game'', is a 2013 mobile game adaptation in which players enact the protagonist's actions to recreate Poe's story on Google Play<ref>{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.learnvideogames.poe&hl=en |title=Poe's Tell-Tale Heart:The Game - Android Apps on Google Play |website=Play.google.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref> and Apple iOS.\n* The 2015 animated anthology ''Extraordinary Tales'' includes \"The Tell-Tale Heart\", narrated by [[Bela Lugosi]].\n* The 2015 [[Lifetime movie]] ''The Murder Pact'', starring [[Alexa Vega]], is based on Poe's work and incorporates allusions to it, such as the \"vulture eye\" from \"The Tell-Tale Heart\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Traciy Reyes |url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2411726/the-murder-pact-lifetime-movie-tell-tale-lies-lindsey-stirling-music-trailer-not-true-story/ |title=\u2018The Murder Pact\u2019: Lifetime Movie, Also Known As \u2018Tell-Tale Lies\u2019, Airs Tonight Featuring Music By Lindsey Stirling |website=Inquisitr.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-16}}</ref>\n* In April 2016, a film adaption directed by John Le Tier was released, entitled \"The Tell-Tale Heart\". It starred Peter Bogdonavich, Rose McGowan, and Patrick John Flueger in the lead role. It featured a full narration of Poe's story with added elements imagining the narrator as a former tortured soldier with PTSD.\n* In spring 2017, [[Udon Entertainment]]'s Manga Classics line will publish ''The Stories of Edgar Allan Poe'', which will include a manga format adaptation of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\".<ref>[http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-07-21/udon-ent-to-release-street-fighter-novel-dragon-crown-manga/.104545 \"Udon Ent. to Release Street Fighter Novel, Dragon's Crown Manga\"], Anime News Network, July 21, 2016</ref>\n* In December 2018, [[Anthony Neilson]]'s stage adaptation was presented at London's [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Malvern |first1=Jack |title=Edgar Allen Poe\u2019s horror classic The Tell\u2011Tale Heart back from the dead after attic clear\u2011out |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/edgar-allen-poe-s-horror-classic-the-tell-tale-heart-back-from-the-dead-after-attic-clear-out-8bz8jdljs |work=[[The Times]] |date=23 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n* The language-learning service [[Duolingo]]\u2019s website features a six-part version of Poe\u2019s story in Spanish, dramatically narrated and with interactive prompts for learners to use to test their Spanish knowledge.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|Mystery Tales of Edgar Allan Poe/The Tell-Tale Heart|The Tell-Tale Heart}}\n{{Commonscat}}\n* [https://www.poemuseum.org/works-telltale.php \"The Poe Museum\"] - Full text of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\"\n* [http://www.eapoe.org/works/tales/thearta.htm \"The Tell-Tale Heart\"] - Full text of the first printing, from the ''Pioneer'', 1843\n* [http://www.escape-suspense.com/2007/10/the-tell-tale-h.html Mid-20th century radio adaptations of \"The Tell-Tale Heart\"]\n* [http://www.shmoop.com/tell-tale-heart/ \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" study guide and teaching guide] - themes, analysis, quotes, teacher resources\n* [http://www.TheTell-TaleHeart.com \"The Tell-Tale Heart\" animation] - Award-winning 2010 animated movie, teacher resources, student games\n* [https://librivox.org/search?q=The%20Tell-Tale%20Heart&search_form=advanced 20 LibriVox audiorecordings, read by various readers]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/pioneerliteraryc01lowe#page/n5/mode/2up The Pioneer, January, 1843, Boston edition.]\n{{Edgar Allan Poe}}\n{{The Tell-Tale Heart}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tell-Tale Heart, The}}\n[[Category:1843 short stories]]\n[[Category:Horror short stories]]\n[[Category:Fiction with unreliable narrators]]\n[[Category:Short stories adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Short stories by Edgar Allan Poe]]\n", "name_user": "Hziegerhofer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot summary:made the sentence more thorough.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Tell-Tale_Heart"}
{"title_page": "Heanor Gate Science College", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK school \n| name          = Heanor Gate Science College\n| image         = Heanor gate science college.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|53.01106|-1.37081|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = Aspire Learn Achieve\n| established   = 1964\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Principal\n| head          = Reece Allen\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = Chair\n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = [[Science College]]\n| address        = Kirkley Drive\n| city          = [[Heanor]]\n| county        = [[Derbyshire]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = DE75 7RA\n| local_authority           = \n| ofsted        = yes\n| urn           = 137606\n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = 1337\n| gender        = [[Coeducation|Mixed]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = Former names\n| free_1        = Heanor Gate Comprehensive School<br />Heanor Gate School\n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.heanorgate.org.uk\n}}\n'''Heanor Gate Science College''' is a medium-sized secondary [[Academy (English school)|academy school]] and specialist [[Science College]] located in [[Heanor]] in the [[Amber Valley]] district of [[Derbyshire]], England. Although in 2012 the school achieved an \"outstanding\" [[Ofsted]] report, in 2013 the school was downgraded to \"inadequate\", which resulted in the school being placed in special measures. hi alllll!\n\n==History==\nIt opened in September 1964 as Heanor Gate County Secondary School, a [[secondary modern school]] being officially opened on 19 June 1965. In the 1990s, it became a grant maintained school. It became a foundation school, very similar to grant maintained status, and added a sixth form. In 2002, it gained [[Science College]] specialist status, the first in Derbyshire. This was incorporated into the school's name from October 2002. The school converted to an Academy in November 2011. The school then became part of the Spencer Academies Trust from September 2014.<ref>[http://www.heanorgate.org.uk/page/?title=History+of+the+School&pid=100 Heanor Gate website (History page)]</ref>\n\n===Former schools===\nOther schools that combined together to produce the school include Heanor Grammar School on ''Mundy Street'', the William Howitt Secondary Modern School on ''Loscoe Road'' and Loscoe Road Girls Secondary Modern School. The former grammar school became the [[South East Derbyshire College]] in 1976.\n\n===School buildings===\nIn February 2010<ref>http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/heanor-school-left-pick-pieces-multi-million-pound-blaze/story-11607500-detail/story.html</ref> the Art and Technology block (H block) suffered a devastating fire caused by an electrical fault, which resulted in the Art section of the building being completely destroyed. This section of the block was consequently removed and replaced with a covered work area for the construction students. The Art block was subsequently moved to the newly built N block. This block then received an extension in 2012.\n\nIn 2013 the Science block (F block) was completely refurbished to provide new and improved science facilities for the school.\n\nThe Sixth From block (S block) was also refurbished in 2014 to provide a larger space for the students and some new class rooms.\n\nA new Student Support block (T block) was also constructed in 2014 to provide better facilities for students requiring educational support or help during school life from the school.\n\n==Admissions==\nThe school accepts children aged 11\u201316. The Post 16 Centre (Sixth Form) is for ages 16\u201318.\n\n==School buildings==\nThe school has a total of 15 blocks, some part of the original school, although some are temporary buildings.<ref>[http://www.heanorgate.org.uk/page/?title=Plan+of+the+School&pid=352 Heanor Gate Plan]</ref>\n\nA block- Admin and Reception\n\nB block- Performing arts, PE, Hall and Gym\n\nC block- Library, Careers & Support Centre\n\nD block- Maths, English and Computer Suites\n\nE block- Maths, English, Business and Computer Suites\n\nF block- Sciences (Physics and Chemistry)\n\nG block- Biology & Social Sciences\n\nH block- Technology (part of the original art building was destroyed in the fire)\n\nJ block- Humanities\n\nK block- Languages\n\nL block- Beauty Salon, Achievement Centre and Computer Suites\n\nM block- Music\n\nN block- Art & Design\n\nS block- Sixth Form Centre & Sociology\n\nT block- Student Support\n\n==House system==\n\nThe school currently has 5 houses named after Derbyshire's Stately Homes.\n\nChatsworth- Red, Haddon- Yellow, Hardwick- Green, Kedleston- Purple and Sudbury- Blue\n\nPrior to this the school had 4 'houses' each one named after a person of note.\n\nRoyce House-Red, Shaftesbury House-Yellow, Pastuer House-Blue and Nightingale House-Green\n<ref>former pupil</ref>\n\n==Academic performance==\nIt gets [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] results at about the average for comprehensive schools in England, but slightly below average for Derbyshire. A level results are slightly under the England average.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.heanorgate.org.uk Heanor Gate Science College website]\n* [http://www.heanorgate.org.uk/page/?title=History+of+the+School&pid=100 Heanor Gate Science College History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070621175054/http://www.btinternet.com/~meeknet/HGRE/ Religious Education]\n* [http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/display/(id)/94419 Inspection Report]. [[Ofsted]] (27 March 2008).\n* [http://www.edubase.gov.uk/establishment/summary.xhtml?urn=112993 EduBase]\n\n===News items===\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1418193/Boys-dancing-dreams-shattered-by-bullies.html Ballet dancer injured in 2003]\n* [http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Heanor-school-left-pick-pieces-multi-million-pound-blaze/story-11607500-detail/story.html Art block (H block) burnt down in 2010]\n\n{{Schools in Derbyshire}}\n\n[[Category:Academies in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Derbyshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK school \n| name          = Heanor Gate Science College\n| image         = Heanor gate science college.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|53.01106|-1.37081|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n| motto         = Aspire Learn Achieve\n| established   = 1964\n| closed        = \n| type          = [[Academy (English school)|Academy]]\n| religious_affiliation      = \n| president     = \n| head_label    = Principal\n| head          = Reece Allen\n| r_head_label  = \n| r_head        = \n| chair_label   = Chair\n| chair         = \n| founder       = \n| specialist    = [[Science College]]\n| address        = Kirkley Drive\n| city          = [[Heanor]]\n| county        = [[Derbyshire]]\n| country       = England\n| postcode      = DE75 7RA\n| local_authority           = \n| ofsted        = yes\n| urn           = 137606\n| staff         = \n| enrolment    = 1337\n| gender        = [[Coeducation|Mixed]]\n| lower_age     = 11\n| upper_age     = 18\n| houses        = \n| colours       = \n| publication   = \n| free_label_1  = Former names\n| free_1        = Heanor Gate Comprehensive School<br />Heanor Gate School\n| free_label_2  = \n| free_2        = \n| free_label_3  = \n| free_3        = \n| website       = http://www.heanorgate.org.uk\n}}\n'''Heanor Gate Science College''' is a medium-sized secondary [[Academy (English school)|academy school]] and specialist [[Science College]] located in [[Heanor]] in the [[Amber Valley]] district of [[Derbyshire]], England. Although in 2012 the school achieved an \"outstanding\" [[Ofsted]] report, in 2013 the school was downgraded to \"inadequate\", which resulted in the school being placed in special measures.\n\n==History==\nIt opened in September 1964 as Heanor Gate County Secondary School, a [[secondary modern school]] being officially opened on 19 June 1965. In the 1990s, it became a grant maintained school. It became a foundation school, very similar to grant maintained status, and added a sixth form. In 2002, it gained [[Science College]] specialist status, the first in Derbyshire. This was incorporated into the school's name from October 2002. The school converted to an Academy in November 2011. The school then became part of the Spencer Academies Trust from September 2014.<ref>[http://www.heanorgate.org.uk/page/?title=History+of+the+School&pid=100 Heanor Gate website (History page)]</ref>\n\n===Former schools===\nOther schools that combined together to produce the school include Heanor Grammar School on ''Mundy Street'', the William Howitt Secondary Modern School on ''Loscoe Road'' and Loscoe Road Girls Secondary Modern School. The former grammar school became the [[South East Derbyshire College]] in 1976.\n\n===School buildings===\nIn February 2010<ref>http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/heanor-school-left-pick-pieces-multi-million-pound-blaze/story-11607500-detail/story.html</ref> the Art and Technology block (H block) suffered a devastating fire caused by an electrical fault, which resulted in the Art section of the building being completely destroyed. This section of the block was consequently removed and replaced with a covered work area for the construction students. The Art block was subsequently moved to the newly built N block. This block then received an extension in 2012.\n\nIn 2013 the Science block (F block) was completely refurbished to provide new and improved science facilities for the school.\n\nThe Sixth From block (S block) was also refurbished in 2014 to provide a larger space for the students and some new class rooms.\n\nA new Student Support block (T block) was also constructed in 2014 to provide better facilities for students requiring educational support or help during school life from the school.\n\n==Admissions==\nThe school accepts children aged 11\u201316. The Post 16 Centre (Sixth Form) is for ages 16\u201318.\n\n==School buildings==\nThe school has a total of 15 blocks, some part of the original school, although some are temporary buildings.<ref>[http://www.heanorgate.org.uk/page/?title=Plan+of+the+School&pid=352 Heanor Gate Plan]</ref>\n\nA block- Admin and Reception\n\nB block- Performing arts, PE, Hall and Gym\n\nC block- Library, Careers & Support Centre\n\nD block- Maths, English and Computer Suites\n\nE block- Maths, English, Business and Computer Suites\n\nF block- Sciences (Physics and Chemistry)\n\nG block- Biology & Social Sciences\n\nH block- Technology (part of the original art building was destroyed in the fire)\n\nJ block- Humanities\n\nK block- Languages\n\nL block- Beauty Salon, Achievement Centre and Computer Suites\n\nM block- Music\n\nN block- Art & Design\n\nS block- Sixth Form Centre & Sociology\n\nT block- Student Support\n\n==House system==\n\nThe school currently has 5 houses named after Derbyshire's Stately Homes.\n\nChatsworth- Red, Haddon- Yellow, Hardwick- Green, Kedleston- Purple and Sudbury- Blue\n\nPrior to this the school had 4 'houses' each one named after a person of note.\n\nRoyce House-Red, Shaftesbury House-Yellow, Pastuer House-Blue and Nightingale House-Green\n<ref>former pupil</ref>\n\n==Academic performance==\nIt gets [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] results at about the average for comprehensive schools in England, but slightly below average for Derbyshire. A level results are slightly under the England average.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.heanorgate.org.uk Heanor Gate Science College website]\n* [http://www.heanorgate.org.uk/page/?title=History+of+the+School&pid=100 Heanor Gate Science College History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070621175054/http://www.btinternet.com/~meeknet/HGRE/ Religious Education]\n* [http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/oxedu_reports/display/(id)/94419 Inspection Report]. [[Ofsted]] (27 March 2008).\n* [http://www.edubase.gov.uk/establishment/summary.xhtml?urn=112993 EduBase]\n\n===News items===\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1418193/Boys-dancing-dreams-shattered-by-bullies.html Ballet dancer injured in 2003]\n* [http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Heanor-school-left-pick-pieces-multi-million-pound-blaze/story-11607500-detail/story.html Art block (H block) burnt down in 2010]\n\n{{Schools in Derbyshire}}\n\n[[Category:Academies in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Derbyshire]]\n", "name_user": "92.8.215.237", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heanor_Gate_Science_College"}
{"title_page": "Pipistrel Alpha Trainer", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|Slovenian light-sport aircraft}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n | name=Alpha Trainer\n | image= File:F-WLAB Pipistrel Alpha Electro 3 (cropped).jpg\n | caption= Pipistrel Alpha in flight\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n | type=[[Light-sport aircraft]]\n | national origin=[[Slovenia]]\n | manufacturer=[[Pipistrel]]\n | designer=\n | first flight=\n | introduced=\n | retired=\n | status=In production\n | primary user=\n | more users= <!--Limited to three in total; separate using <br /> -->\n | produced= May 2012 \u2013 present\n | number built=\n | program cost= <!--Total program cost-->\n | unit cost= [[US$]]103,000 (2014)\n | developed from= [[Pipistrel Virus]]\n | variants with their own articles=\n}}\n|}\nThe '''Pipistrel Alpha Trainer''' is a [[Slovenia]]n [[light-sport aircraft]] intended specifically for [[flight training]], designed and produced by [[Pipistrel]].<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/PipistrelPromises83KLSATrainer_205813-1.html|title = Pipistrel Promises $83K LSA Trainer|accessdate = 1 December 2011|last = Grady|first = Mary|date = 30 November 2011| work = AVweb}}</ref><ref name=\"Grady14May12\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/PipistrelAlphaLSATrainerReadyToFlyFor85K_206688-1.html |title = Pipistrel Alpha LSA Trainer Ready To Fly For $85K|accessdate = 17 May 2012|last = Grady|first = Mary|date = 14 May 2012| work = AVweb}}</ref>\n\nThe Alpha was announced at the end of 2011 and production started in 2012.<ref name=\"WDLA15\">Tacke, Willi; Marino Boric; et al: ''World Directory of Light Aviation 2015\u201316'', page 73. Flying Pages Europe SARL, 2015. {{ISSN|1368-485X}}</ref>\n\n==Design and development==\n[[File:Z-Pipistrel Alpha Trainer 535D (46779464715).jpg|thumb|The Rotax-powered Alpha Trainer]] \n\nThe aircraft was designed to comply with the US light-sport aircraft rules. It features a cantilever [[high-wing]], a two-seats in [[side-by-side configuration]], [[tricycle landing gear]] and a single {{convert|80|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[Rotax 912 UL]] engine in [[tractor configuration]].<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\" />\n\nThe aircraft is made from composites and features landing gear especially designed for training use. A [[ballistic parachute]] is standard equipment along with traditional and cheaper round-dial style [[flight instruments]], rather than a [[glass cockpit]]. The design goals include economy of purchase and operation and its initial price of [[US$]]85,000 was intended to address moves by Pipistrel's competition in raising prices on their aircraft. In particular the Alpha's price was initially set well below the then-current US$149,000 price announced for the comparable [[Cessna 162]], although by 2014 Pipistrel had raised the price to [[US$]]103,000. The fuel consumption is projected to be 2.5 US gallons per hour (9.5 litres per hour) when used in the training role and conducting doing touch-and-go circuits.<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\" /><ref name=\"Grady14May12\" />\n<!-- ==Operational history== -->\n\n==Variants==\n===Alpha Electro===\n[[File:Pipistrel Alpha Electro at AERO Friedrichshafen 2018 (1X7A4773).jpg|thumb|Alpha Electro]]\n{{ external media\n|align=left\n| video1 =[http://www.avweb.com/videos/Video-Pipistrel-Alpha-Electro-Aero-2015-223855-1.html Video: Pipistrel Alpha Electro Aero 2015]\n| video2 =[http://www.avweb.com/videos/Video-Flying-Pipistrels-Electric-Airplane-224345-1.html Video: Flying Pipistrel's Electric Airplane]\n}}\nPipistrel introduced an electric version called the Alpha Electro in 2015 at a price of 69,000 euros,<ref name=\"WDLA15\"/> with technology from the [[Pipistrel WATTsUP]] proof of concept design, for [[Airfield traffic pattern|short training]]. It has energy for one flight hour plus reserves, and can recharge in 45 minutes or have its batteries replaced in 5 minutes.<ref name=avw2015-04-14>{{cite web |first=Mary |last=Grady |url=http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Introduces-Alpha-Electro-223852-1.html |title=Pipistrel Introduces Alpha Electro |work=avweb.com|agency=Aviation Publishing Group |date=14 April 2015 |accessdate=15 April 2015 }}</ref> Instead of 78&nbsp;lb (35.5&nbsp;kg) of fuel, it has 277 pounds (126&nbsp;kg) of [[Lithium polymer battery|LiPo cells]], however the water cooled electric motor weighs 11&nbsp;kg;<ref name=avw2015-06>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Bertorelli |url=http://www.avweb.com/blogs/insider/An-Electric-Airplane-Virgin-No-More-224286-1.html |title=An Electric Airplane Virgin No More |work=avweb.com| agency=Aviation Publishing Group |date=17 June 2015 |accessdate=21 June 2015 }}</ref> much less than the gasoline engine. It has a useful load of 380&nbsp;lb, whereas a [[Cessna 152]] has between 350\u2013480&nbsp;lb useful load.<ref name=avw2015-03>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Bertorelli |url=http://www.avweb.com/blogs/insider/Will-2015-See-Deliverable-Electric-Airplanes-223695-1.html |title=Will 2015 See Deliverable Electric Airplanes? |work=avweb.com|agency=Aviation Publishing Group |date=15 March 2015 |accessdate=4 April 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"Grady14Apr15\">{{cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r1Nw12YNqfY|title = Pipistrel Alpha Electro Aero 2015 |accessdate = 20 April 2015|last = Grady|first = Mary|work=AVweb|date = 14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter 38 minutes of flying various manoeuvres,<!--English spelling--> battery charge may be 25%. From the inside, the Electro is very similar to the gasoline-powered version, but from the outside, the Electro is much quieter. Electricity costs are about 1/10 of gasoline.<!--European context--><ref name=avw2015-06/>\n\nThe Electro is now certified in the USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2018/04/27/all-electric-trainer-plane-airworthiness-certification-faa-us|title=First all-electric trainer plane gets airworthiness certification from the FAA in the US|last=Lambert|first=Fred|work=Electrek|accessdate=27 April 2018|date=27 April 2018}}</ref> In 2015 Pipistrel intended to fly the Electro from France to England two days before the [[Airbus_E-Fan#Operational_history|Airbus E-Fan]], but was prevented by Siemens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Cancels-Channel-Flight-After-Siemens-Pulls-Support-224400-1.html|title=Pipistrel Cancels Channel Flight After Siemens Pulls Support|last=Niles|first=Russ|work=AVweb|accessdate=2 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728082854/http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Cancels-Channel-Flight-After-Siemens-Pulls-Support-224400-1.html|archivedate=28 July 2015|date=7 July 2015}}</ref>  Four Electro aircraft will be used to provide flight training in Fresno, California starting in late 2017 as part of the [[Sustainable Aviation Project]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2016/october/19/electric-aviation-made-practical |title = Electric Aviation Made Practical |accessdate = 18 February 2017|date = 19 October 2016 }}</ref>{{needs update|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Operators==\n* WorldWide Wings \u2013 15 on order for use in the school's locations in California and Florida, United States.<ref name=\"Grady10Apr18\">{{cite web|url = https://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Lands-Biggest-US-Order-230617-1.html|title = Pipistrel Lands Biggest U.S. Order|accessdate = 12 April 2018|last = Grady |first = Mary|work = AVweb|date = 10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Specifications (Alpha Trainer) ==\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=AVweb and Pipistrel<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\" /><ref name=\"Grady14May12\" /><ref name=\"Alpha\">{{Cite web|url = http://pipistrel-usa.com/models/alpha-trainer.html|title = Pipistrel introduces a fully equipped training aircraft for under $85,000 US|accessdate = 1 December 2011|last = [[Pipistrel]] |date = 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Technical Data\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.pipistrel.si/plane/alpha-trainer/technical-data|title = Alpha Trainer Technical Data|accessdate = 21 June 2016|work = pipistrel.si|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160302161335/www.pipistrel.si/plane/alpha-trainer/technical-data|archivedate = 2 March 2016}}</ref>\n|prime units?=kts<!-- imp or kts first for US aircraft, and UK aircraft pre-metrification, met(ric) first for all others. You MUST choose a format, or no specifications will show -->\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|genhide=\n\n|crew=one\n|capacity=one passenger\n|length m=\n|length ft=\n|length in=\n|length note=\n|span m=\n|span ft=34\n|span in=6\n|span note=\n|height m=\n|height ft=\n|height in=\n|height note=\n|wing area sqm=\n|wing area sqft=\n|wing area note=\n|aspect ratio=\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight kg=\n|empty weight lb=\n|empty weight note=\n|gross weight kg=\n|gross weight lb=\n|gross weight note=\n|fuel capacity={{convert|13|u.s.gal}}\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=1\n|eng1 name=[[Rotax 912UL]]\n|eng1 type=four cylinder, [[horizontally opposed]], [[four stroke]] aircraft engine\n|eng1 kw=<!-- prop engines -->\n|eng1 hp=80<!-- prop engines -->\n\n|prop blade number=2<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop name=Pipistrel custom wood and composite\n|prop dia m=<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop dia ft=<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop dia in=63<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop note=\n\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|perfhide=\n\n|max speed kmh=\n|max speed mph=\n|max speed kts=\n|max speed note=\n|cruise speed kmh=\n|cruise speed mph=\n|cruise speed kts=108\n|cruise speed note=\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=\n|stall speed note=\n|never exceed speed kmh=\n|never exceed speed mph=\n|never exceed speed kts=\n|never exceed speed note=\n|range km=\n|range miles=\n|range nmi=324\n|range note=\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=\n|ceiling ft=\n|ceiling note=\n|g limits=\n|roll rate=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|glide ratio=<!-- sailplanes -->\n|climb rate ms=\n|climb rate ftmin=\n|climb rate note=\n|time to altitude=\n|sink rate ms=\n|sink rate ftmin=\n|sink rate note=\n|lift to drag=\n|wing loading kg/m2=\n|wing loading lb/sqft=\n|wing loading note=\n|power/mass=\n|thrust/weight=\n|more performance=\n|avionics=\n*[[Garmin]] Aera 500 [[GPS]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n<!-- include as many lines are appropriate. additional lines/entries with carriage return. -->\n|see also=\n|related=<!-- related developments -->\n|similar aircraft=\n*[[Cessna 162]]\n|lists=<!-- related lists -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Pipistrel Alpha Trainer}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.pipistrel.si/plane/alpha-trainer/overview}}\n{{Pipistrel aircraft}}\n\n[[Category:2010s Slovenian civil utility aircraft]]\n[[Category:Single-engined tractor aircraft]]\n[[Category:Light-sport aircraft]]\n[[Category:High-wing aircraft]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|Slovenian light-sport aircraft}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n | name=Alpha Trainer\n | image= File:F-WLAB Pipistrel Alpha Electro 3 (cropped).jpg\n | caption= Pipistrel Alpha in flight\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n | type=[[Light-sport aircraft]]\n | national origin=[[Slovenia]]\n | manufacturer=[[Pipistrel]]\n | designer=\n | first flight=\n | introduced=\n | retired=\n | status=In production\n | primary user=\n | more users= <!--Limited to three in total; separate using <br /> -->\n | produced= May 2012 \u2013 present\n | number built=\n | program cost= <!--Total program cost-->\n | unit cost= [[US$]]103,000 (2014)\n | developed from= [[Pipistrel Virus]]\n | variants with their own articles=\n}}\n|}\nThe '''Pipistrel Alpha Trainer''' is a [[Slovenia]]n [[light-sport aircraft]] intended specifically for [[flight training]], designed and produced by [[Pipistrel]].<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/PipistrelPromises83KLSATrainer_205813-1.html|title = Pipistrel Promises $83K LSA Trainer|accessdate = 1 December 2011|last = Grady|first = Mary|date = 30 November 2011| work = AVweb}}</ref><ref name=\"Grady14May12\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/PipistrelAlphaLSATrainerReadyToFlyFor85K_206688-1.html |title = Pipistrel Alpha LSA Trainer Ready To Fly For $85K|accessdate = 17 May 2012|last = Grady|first = Mary|date = 14 May 2012| work = AVweb}}</ref>\n\nThe Alpha was announced at the end of 2011 and production started in 2012.<ref name=\"WDLA15\">Tacke, Willi; Marino Boric; et al: ''World Directory of Light Aviation 2015\u201316'', page 73. Flying Pages Europe SARL, 2015. {{ISSN|1368-485X}}</ref>\n\n==Design and development==\n[[File:Z-Pipistrel Alpha Trainer 535D (46779464715).jpg|thumb|The Rotax-powered Alpha Trainer]] \n\nThe aircraft was designed to comply with the US light-sport aircraft rules. It features a cantilever [[high-wing]], a two-seats in [[side-by-side configuration]], [[tricycle landing gear]] and a single {{convert|80|hp|kW|0|abbr=on}} [[Rotax 912UL]] engine in [[tractor configuration]].<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\" />\n\nThe aircraft is made from composites and features landing gear especially designed for training use. A [[ballistic parachute]] is standard equipment along with traditional and cheaper round-dial style [[flight instruments]], rather than a [[glass cockpit]]. The design goals include economy of purchase and operation and its initial price of [[US$]]85,000 was intended to address moves by Pipistrel's competition in raising prices on their aircraft. In particular the Alpha's price was initially set well below the then-current US$149,000 price announced for the comparable [[Cessna 162]], although by 2014 Pipistrel had raised the price to [[US$]]103,000. The fuel consumption is projected to be 2.5 US gallons per hour (9.5 litres per hour) when used in the training role and conducting doing touch-and-go circuits.<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\" /><ref name=\"Grady14May12\" />\n<!-- ==Operational history== -->\n\n==Variants==\n===Alpha Electro===\n[[File:Pipistrel Alpha Electro at AERO Friedrichshafen 2018 (1X7A4773).jpg|thumb|Alpha Electro]]\n{{ external media\n|align=left\n| video1 =[http://www.avweb.com/videos/Video-Pipistrel-Alpha-Electro-Aero-2015-223855-1.html Video: Pipistrel Alpha Electro Aero 2015]\n| video2 =[http://www.avweb.com/videos/Video-Flying-Pipistrels-Electric-Airplane-224345-1.html Video: Flying Pipistrel's Electric Airplane]\n}}\nPipistrel introduced an electric version called the Alpha Electro in 2015 at a price of 69,000 euros,<ref name=\"WDLA15\"/> with technology from the [[Pipistrel WATTsUP]] proof of concept design, for [[Airfield traffic pattern|short training]]. It has energy for one flight hour plus reserves, and can recharge in 45 minutes or have its batteries replaced in 5 minutes.<ref name=avw2015-04-14>{{cite web |first=Mary |last=Grady |url=http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Introduces-Alpha-Electro-223852-1.html |title=Pipistrel Introduces Alpha Electro |work=avweb.com|agency=Aviation Publishing Group |date=14 April 2015 |accessdate=15 April 2015 }}</ref> Instead of 78&nbsp;lb (35.5&nbsp;kg) of fuel, it has 277 pounds (126&nbsp;kg) of [[Lithium polymer battery|LiPo cells]], however the water cooled electric motor weighs 11&nbsp;kg;<ref name=avw2015-06>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Bertorelli |url=http://www.avweb.com/blogs/insider/An-Electric-Airplane-Virgin-No-More-224286-1.html |title=An Electric Airplane Virgin No More |work=avweb.com| agency=Aviation Publishing Group |date=17 June 2015 |accessdate=21 June 2015 }}</ref> much less than the gasoline engine. It has a useful load of 380&nbsp;lb, whereas a [[Cessna 152]] has between 350\u2013480&nbsp;lb useful load.<ref name=avw2015-03>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Bertorelli |url=http://www.avweb.com/blogs/insider/Will-2015-See-Deliverable-Electric-Airplanes-223695-1.html |title=Will 2015 See Deliverable Electric Airplanes? |work=avweb.com|agency=Aviation Publishing Group |date=15 March 2015 |accessdate=4 April 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"Grady14Apr15\">{{cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r1Nw12YNqfY|title = Pipistrel Alpha Electro Aero 2015 |accessdate = 20 April 2015|last = Grady|first = Mary|work=AVweb|date = 14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter 38 minutes of flying various manoeuvres,<!--English spelling--> battery charge may be 25%. From the inside, the Electro is very similar to the gasoline-powered version, but from the outside, the Electro is much quieter. Electricity costs are about 1/10 of gasoline.<!--European context--><ref name=avw2015-06/>\n\nThe Electro is now certified in the USA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2018/04/27/all-electric-trainer-plane-airworthiness-certification-faa-us|title=First all-electric trainer plane gets airworthiness certification from the FAA in the US|last=Lambert|first=Fred|work=Electrek|accessdate=27 April 2018|date=27 April 2018}}</ref> In 2015 Pipistrel intended to fly the Electro from France to England two days before the [[Airbus_E-Fan#Operational_history|Airbus E-Fan]], but was prevented by Siemens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Cancels-Channel-Flight-After-Siemens-Pulls-Support-224400-1.html|title=Pipistrel Cancels Channel Flight After Siemens Pulls Support|last=Niles|first=Russ|work=AVweb|accessdate=2 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728082854/http://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Cancels-Channel-Flight-After-Siemens-Pulls-Support-224400-1.html|archivedate=28 July 2015|date=7 July 2015}}</ref>  Four Electro aircraft will be used to provide flight training in Fresno, California starting in late 2017 as part of the [[Sustainable Aviation Project]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2016/october/19/electric-aviation-made-practical |title = Electric Aviation Made Practical |accessdate = 18 February 2017|date = 19 October 2016 }}</ref>{{needs update|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Operators==\n* WorldWide Wings \u2013 15 on order for use in the school's locations in California and Florida, United States.<ref name=\"Grady10Apr18\">{{cite web|url = https://www.avweb.com/avwebflash/news/Pipistrel-Lands-Biggest-US-Order-230617-1.html|title = Pipistrel Lands Biggest U.S. Order|accessdate = 12 April 2018|last = Grady |first = Mary|work = AVweb|date = 10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Specifications (Alpha Trainer) ==\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=AVweb and Pipistrel<ref name=\"Grady30Nov11\" /><ref name=\"Grady14May12\" /><ref name=\"Alpha\">{{Cite web|url = http://pipistrel-usa.com/models/alpha-trainer.html|title = Pipistrel introduces a fully equipped training aircraft for under $85,000 US|accessdate = 1 December 2011|last = [[Pipistrel]] |date = 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Technical Data\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.pipistrel.si/plane/alpha-trainer/technical-data|title = Alpha Trainer Technical Data|accessdate = 21 June 2016|work = pipistrel.si|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160302161335/www.pipistrel.si/plane/alpha-trainer/technical-data|archivedate = 2 March 2016}}</ref>\n|prime units?=kts<!-- imp or kts first for US aircraft, and UK aircraft pre-metrification, met(ric) first for all others. You MUST choose a format, or no specifications will show -->\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|genhide=\n\n|crew=one\n|capacity=one passenger\n|length m=\n|length ft=\n|length in=\n|length note=\n|span m=\n|span ft=34\n|span in=6\n|span note=\n|height m=\n|height ft=\n|height in=\n|height note=\n|wing area sqm=\n|wing area sqft=\n|wing area note=\n|aspect ratio=\n|airfoil=\n|empty weight kg=\n|empty weight lb=\n|empty weight note=\n|gross weight kg=\n|gross weight lb=\n|gross weight note=\n|fuel capacity={{convert|13|u.s.gal}}\n|more general=\n<!--\n        Powerplant\n-->\n|eng1 number=1\n|eng1 name=[[Rotax 912UL]]\n|eng1 type=four cylinder, [[horizontally opposed]], [[four stroke]] aircraft engine\n|eng1 kw=<!-- prop engines -->\n|eng1 hp=80<!-- prop engines -->\n\n|prop blade number=2<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop name=Pipistrel custom wood and composite\n|prop dia m=<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop dia ft=<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop dia in=63<!-- propeller aircraft -->\n|prop note=\n\n<!--\n        Performance\n-->\n|perfhide=\n\n|max speed kmh=\n|max speed mph=\n|max speed kts=\n|max speed note=\n|cruise speed kmh=\n|cruise speed mph=\n|cruise speed kts=108\n|cruise speed note=\n|stall speed kmh=\n|stall speed mph=\n|stall speed kts=\n|stall speed note=\n|never exceed speed kmh=\n|never exceed speed mph=\n|never exceed speed kts=\n|never exceed speed note=\n|range km=\n|range miles=\n|range nmi=324\n|range note=\n|endurance=<!-- if range unknown -->\n|ceiling m=\n|ceiling ft=\n|ceiling note=\n|g limits=\n|roll rate=<!-- aerobatic -->\n|glide ratio=<!-- sailplanes -->\n|climb rate ms=\n|climb rate ftmin=\n|climb rate note=\n|time to altitude=\n|sink rate ms=\n|sink rate ftmin=\n|sink rate note=\n|lift to drag=\n|wing loading kg/m2=\n|wing loading lb/sqft=\n|wing loading note=\n|power/mass=\n|thrust/weight=\n|more performance=\n|avionics=\n*[[Garmin]] Aera 500 [[GPS]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n<!-- include as many lines are appropriate. additional lines/entries with carriage return. -->\n|see also=\n|related=<!-- related developments -->\n|similar aircraft=\n*[[Cessna 162]]\n|lists=<!-- related lists -->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Pipistrel Alpha Trainer}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.pipistrel.si/plane/alpha-trainer/overview}}\n{{Pipistrel aircraft}}\n\n[[Category:2010s Slovenian civil ut