{"title_page": "9th National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam", "text_new": "{{Infobox historical event\n  |Event_Name     = 9th National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam\n  |Image_Name     = Flag of the Communist Party of Vietnam.svg\n  |Imagesize      = 250px\n  |Image_Alt      = CPV's flag\n  |Image_Caption  = The flag of the Communist Party of Vietnam \n  |Thumb_Time     = \n  |Participants   = 1,168 delegates (which includes the members of the 8th Central Committee)\n  |Location       = Ba \u0110\u00ecnh Hall\n  |Date           = 19\u201322 April 2001 (4 days)\n  |Result         = The election of the [[9th Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|9th Central Committee]]\n  |URL            = \n}}\nThe '''9th National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam''' ({{lang-vi|\u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ed9i \u0110\u1ea3ng C\u1ed9ng s\u1ea3n Vi\u1ec7t Nam IX}}) was held in Ba \u0110\u00ecnh Hall, [[Hanoi]] from 19\u201322 April 2001.  The congress occurs once every five years. A total of 1,168 delegates represented the party's 2,479,719 card-carrying members.\n\n==Preparations==\n\n===Dismissals and reassignments===\nPlanning for the 9th National Congress began in August 1999 at the 7th plenum of the [[8th Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|8th Central Committee]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=181}} Preparatory work for the congress began at the 8th plenum of the 8th Central Committee \"by assigning various organizational tasks to senior party officials.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=181}} After the 8th plenum several officials lost their post because of either disciplinary cases, government reshuffling or reassignment within the party.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=181}} These changes were implemented because of widespread criticism of the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]]'s (CPV) tackling of corruption, and in order to strengthen the coherence of national policy and its implementation.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} A statement issued by the 8th plenum stated that [[Ng\u00f4 Xu\u00e2n L\u1ed9c]], a [[Deputy Prime Minister of Vietnam|Deputy Prime Minister]], and [[Cao S\u0129 Ki\u00eam]], a party official working in the economic sector, had been given disciplinary warnings.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} In addition, the 8th plenum recommended to dismiss Ng\u00f4 Xu\u00e2n L\u1ed9c as a Deputy Prime Minister because of implication in the [[Thanh Long amusement park scandal]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Cao S\u0129 Ki\u00eam on the other hand was criticised for mismanaging loans that resulted in a sudden increase in bad debts.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}}\n\nIn December, the [[National Assembly (Vietnam)|National Assembly]] dismissed Ng\u00f4 Xu\u00e2n L\u1ed9c as Deputy Prime Ministers on the grounds of him being implicated in the Thanh Long scandal and for neglecting his duties.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} [[Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng]], a member of the [[8th Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|8th Politburo]] who held the posts of Deputy Prime Minister and Governor of the [[State Bank of Vietnam|State Bank]], had to relinquish his position as State Bank governor to his deputy [[L\u00ea \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u00fay]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} He was later made First Deputy Prime Minister and became responsible for supervising the works of the three other deputy prime ministers.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Late in January 2001, the [[Standing Committee of the National Assembly|Standing Committee]] of the National Assembly announced that [[Nguy\u1ec5n M\u1ea1nh C\u1ea7m]] had left his position as [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Vietnam)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] so as to be able to concentrate on his duties as  a deputy prime minister.{{#tag:ref|[[Nguy\u1ec5n Dy Ni\u00ean]] succeeded Nguy\u1ec5n M\u1ea1nh C\u1ea7m as foreign minister.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}}|group=note}} [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng \u0110\u00ecnh Tuy\u1ec3n]], the [[Ministry of Trade (Vietnam)|Minister of Trade]], resigned and was succeeded by [[V\u0169 Khoan]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Similar changes occurred within the party organization \u2013 for instance, [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng T\u1ea5n Sang]], the Secretary of the [[Ho Chi Minh City|H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh City]] Party Committee, was reassigned to head the CPV's [[Central Economic Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Economic Commission]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Similar changes occurred with at least seven other party officials.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}}\n\n===L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's downfall===\nDuring 2000, [[L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau]], the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of Vietnam|General Secretary]] of the 8th Central Committee, attempted to shore up support within the party for his reelection for a second term as general secretary.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} The 9th plenum of the 8th Central Committee (10\u201319 April) discussed draft proposals to strengthen the decision-making process at the top of the party.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} Three options were up for discussion; introducing direct elections of the [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Politburo Standing Committee]] by the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Committee]], to reestablish the [[Secretariat of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Secretariat]] (abolished at the [[8th National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam|8th National Congress]]), and the retention of the Politburo Standing Committee while at the same time reviving the Secretariat.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} After a visit to France, L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau reportedly tried to amend the [[Constitution of Vietnam|state constitution]] and the [[Statutes of the Communist Party of Vietnam|CPV statutes]] to as to allow him to serve concurrently as general secretary and [[President of Vietnam|state president]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} His stewardship as general secretary was severely tested by rural unrest, the [[Asian financial crisis]], and the continued influence of the Advisors to the Central Committee, most prominently among them being [[\u0110\u1ed7 M\u01b0\u1eddi]], L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's predecessor as general secretary.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} \u0110\u1ed7 M\u01b0\u1eddi still retained policy influence during L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's term in office, and while he was no longer a member of the [[Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Politburo]], he attended the meetings of the 8th Politburo.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} He was appointed the convenor of the 9th National Congress, a post which gave him considerable influence over congress proceedings.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} Anyway, \u0110\u1ed7 M\u01b0\u1eddi together with [[V\u00f5 V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7t]] and [[L\u00ea \u0110\u1ee9c Anh]] sent a joint letter to the 8th Central Committee which criticized L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's leadership.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}}\n\nThe first session of the 11th plenum of the 8th Central Committee (held in January 2001), issued a statement which said that no one over the age of 65 could be re-elected to the Central Committee, or any other central party position.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} However, after a hard-led counter-offensive by L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau, another statement by the Central Committee was issued which stated that certain exceptions could be made by \"key cadres\".{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau pointed on a wave of demonstrations by ethnic minorities in the Central Highland in February 2001 for a reason to stay in office, so as to assure stability.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} By the end of the second session of the 11th plenum it looked to outsiders that his position was secure.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} In a mid-April Politburo meeting, two-thirds of its members voted to retain L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau as general secretary, but on 17 April at the 12th plenum the Central Committee overturned the politburo's decision (in itself a very rare event) and voted to oust him from office.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}}\n\n===Documents===\nAt the 9th plenum of the 8th Central Committee, attended by the advisors to the Central Committee, discussed the drafting of four documents; the Political Report, the Socioeconomic Strategy for the 2001\u20132010 Period, the [[7th Five-Year Plan (Vietnam)|7th Five-Year Plan]] (2001\u20132005), and the Report on the Revision of the Party Statutes.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} [[Nguy\u1ec5n Ph\u00fa Tr\u1ecdng]], a member of the 8th Politburo and the Secretary of the [[Hanoi]] Party Committee, briefed the 9th plenum on the contentious matter that still needed to be discussed, such as sections of the Political Report and the need for further amendments to the party's statutes.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} The 10th plenum of the 8th Central Committee (26 June \u2013 4 July), according to an official communique, \"laid the ground work for the 9th National Party Congress.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} In the aftermath of the 10th plenum, the Vietnamese media gave increasing attention to internal party discussions and the then confidential political report, ''Bringing into Full Play the Strength of the Entire Nation, Continuing the Renovation Process, Accelerating Industrialization and Modernization, Building and Defending the Socialist Vietnamese Fatherland''.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} The Political Report signalled no major changes from the political report given to the 8th National Congress.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} However, there were some minor changes.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} For instance, previously party documents had stated that the party and state's long term policy was \"to develop the commodity-based multi-sector economy operating in accordance with the state-managed, socialist-orientated market mechanism\", but the political report to the 9th National Congress condensed this into a single phrase, \"to develop a [[socialist-oriented market economy]].\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|pp=184\u2013185}} The political report still gave prominence to [[Ho Chi Minh Thought|H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh Thought]], the [[Socialism (Marxism)|period of transition to socialism]] (which can be shortened by \"orderly steps and big leaps forward\"), the leading role given to the state and cooperatives in the economy, and [[class struggle]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=185}} According to the Political Report, \"The principal content of class struggle is to successfully pursue the goal of industrialization and modernization along the lines of socialism, to struggle to frustrate all schemes and acts of sabotage by hostile forces, and to build Vietnam into a prosperous socialist country.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=185}}\n\n==Delegates==\nDuring the final quarter of 2000, and the beginning of 2001, party congresses were held at grassroots and provincial levels to elect the delegates to the 9th National Congress.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=185}}\n\n==The Congress and the 1st plenum==\nThe 9th National Congress met from 19\u201322 April 2001.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=82}} The elected Central Committee, the [[9th Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|9th]], was composed of 150-members (the 8th Central Committee had 170 members).{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=82}} Of these, 87 had been members of the 8th Central Committee, the rest, 63 in total, were new members.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=82}} The 9th Central Committee comprised primarily incumbent officials who held posts in either the [[Government of Vietnam|central government]] or were provincial leaders.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|pp=82\u201383}} [[L\u00ea Minh H\u01b0\u01a1ng]], a member of the [[9th Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|9th Politburo]] and [[Ministry of Public Security (Vietnam)|Minister of Public Security]], led the five-member security bloc in the Central Committee, while [[L\u00ea H\u1ed3ng Anh]] was a prominent member of the bloc responsible for [[Ministry of Interior (Vietnam)|internal security]].{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} A third group, led by [[Nguy\u1ec5n V\u0103n An]], the head of the [[Central Organizing Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Organizing and Personnel Commission]], led what Carlyle Thayer referred to as the \"personnel bloc\".{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}}\n\nThe 1st plenum of the 9th Central Committee, held on 22 April, elected the 9th Politburo.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The 9th Politburo consisted of 15 members (the 8th Politburo had 19 members).{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng and [[Nguy\u1ec5n Minh Tri\u1ebft]], both considered reformers by outside observers, rose within the Politburo hierarchy, but so did L\u00ea Minh H\u01b0\u01a1ng and Nguy\u1ec5n Ph\u00fa Tr\u1ecdng, who are labelled conservatives by outside observers.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} L\u00ea H\u1ed3ng Anh, the [[Chairman of the Central Inspection Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Chairman]] of the [[Central Inspection Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Inspection Commission]], was a newcomer to the Politburo and was ranked ninth, \"above two incumbent members\".{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} Military representation within the Politburo was reduced from four members in the 8th Politburo to one, General [[Ph\u1ea1m V\u0103n Tr\u00e0]], in the 9th Politburo.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} In contrast, military representation within the Central Committee increased overall from the 8th Central Committee, but with the majority of military members being incumbents.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}}\n\nThe Politburo Standing Committee and the Advisory Council to the Central Committee were abolished at the congress, and the Secretariat was reestablished.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The Secretariat was elected by the 1st plenum of the 9th Central Committee.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The abolishment of the Advisory Council effectively ended the behind-the-scenes influence of senior retirees.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The congress reaffirmed Vietnam's plans of accelerating industrialization and modernization in order to become a modern-industrialized state by 2020, and adopted the 7th Five-Year Plan and the Socioeconomic Strategy for the 2001\u20132010.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=84}} According to Carlyle Thayer, these documents \"called for self-reliance, mobilization of domestic capital, the development of Vietnam's comparative advantage, and attracting external resources in the form of foreign investment capital, new technology, and managerial expertise.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=84}} The Political Report stressed the need to retain good relations with fellow [[socialist state]]s and neighboring countries, while at the same time improving relations with the capitalist world.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|pp=86\u201387}}\n\nL\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau stepped down as general secretary at the 1st plenum, and was succeeded by [[N\u00f4ng \u0110\u1ee9c M\u1ea1nh]].{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} [[Hu Jintao]], the [[Communist Party of China]]'s (CPC) honorary delegate to the 9th National Congress, was rumored for lobbying on L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's retention as general secretary on China's behalf.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=87}} After his election to the general secretaryship, N\u00f4ng \u0110\u1ee9c M\u1ea1nh pledged to Hu Jintao that \"the relationship between Vietnam and China will develop better and better in the days to come.\" Not long after did N\u00f4ng \u0110\u1ee9c M\u1ea1nh meet personally with [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|CPC General Secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]].{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=88}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Abuza|first=Zachary|title=The Lessons of Le Kha Phieu: Changing Rules in Vietnamese politics|pages=121\u2013145|publisher=[[Institute of Southeast Asian Studies]] |journal=[[Contemporary Southeast Asia]] |volume=24  |issue=1|date=April 2002 |url=http://www.vpa-inc.org/conference/pdf/abuza3.pdf |doi=10.1355/cs24-1h|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Thayer |first1=Carlyle |authorlink= |date=January 2001 |title=Vietnam in 2000: Toward the Ninth Party Congress |journal=[[Asian Survey]] | publisher = University of California Press |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=181\u2013188 |doi=10.1525/as.2001.41.1.181|jstor=10.1525/as.2001.41.1.181 |ref=CITEREFThayer2001 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Thayer |first1=Carlyle |authorlink= |date=January 2002 |title=Vietnam in 2001: The Ninth Party Congress and After |journal=[[Asian Survey]] | publisher = University of California Press |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=81\u201389 |doi=10.1525/as.2002.42.1.81|ref=CITEREFThayer2002 |jstor=10.1525/as.2002.42.1.81 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam}}\n\n[[Category:National Congresses of the Communist Party of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:2001 in Vietnam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox historical event\n  |Event_Name     = 9th National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam\n  |Image_Name     = Flag of the Communist Party of Vietnam.svg\n  |Imagesize      = 250px\n  |Image_Alt      = CPV's flag\n  |Image_Caption  = The flag of the Communist Party of Vietnam \n  |Thumb_Time     = \n  |Participants   = 1,168 delegates (which includes the members of the 8th Central Committee)\n  |Location       = Ba \u0110\u00ecnh Hall\n  |Date           = 19\u201322 April 2001 (4 days)\n  |Result         = The election of the [[9th Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|9th Central Committee]]\n  |URL            = \n}}\nThe '''9th National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam''' ({{lang-vi|\u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ed9i \u0110\u1ea3ng C\u1ed9ng s\u1ea3n Vi\u1ec7t Nam IX}}) was held in Ba \u0110\u00ecnh Hall, [[Hanoi]] from 19\u201322 April 2001.  The congress occurs once every five years. A total of 1,168 delegates represented the party's 2,479,719 card-carrying members.\n\n==Preparations==\n\n===Dismissals and reassignments===\nPlanning for the 9th National Congress began in August 1999 at the 7th plenum of the [[8th Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|8th Central Committee]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=181}} Preparatory work for the congress began at the 8th plenum of the 8th Central Committee \"by assigning various organizational tasks to senior party officials.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=181}} After the 8th plenum several officials lost their post because of either disciplinary cases, government reshuffling or reassignment within the party.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=181}} These changes were implemented because of widespread criticism of the [[Communist Party of Vietnam]]'s (CPV) tackling of corruption, and in order to strengthen the coherence of national policy and its implementation.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} A statement issued by the 8th plenum stated that [[Ng\u00f4 Xu\u00e2n L\u1ed9c]], a [[Deputy Prime Minister of Vietnam|Deputy Prime Minister]], and [[Cao S\u0129 Ki\u00eam]], a party official working in the economic sector, had been given disciplinary warnings.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} In addition, the 8th plenum recommended to dismiss Ng\u00f4 Xu\u00e2n L\u1ed9c as a Deputy Prime Minister because of implication in the [[Thanh Long amusement park scandal]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Cao S\u0129 Ki\u00eam on the other hand was criticised for mismanaging loans that resulted in a sudden increase in bad debts.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}}\n\nIn December, the [[National Assembly (Vietnam)|National Assembly]] dismissed Ng\u00f4 Xu\u00e2n L\u1ed9c as Deputy Prime Ministers on the grounds of him being implicated in the Thanh Long scandal and for neglecting his duties.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} [[Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng]], a member of the [[8th Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|8th Politburo]] who held the posts of Deputy Prime Minister and Governor of the [[State Bank of Vietnam|State Bank]], had to relinquish his position as State Bank governor to his deputy [[L\u00ea \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u00fay]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} He was later made First Deputy Prime Minister and became responsible for supervising the works of the three other deputy prime ministers.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Late in January 2001, the [[Standing Committee of the National Assembly|Standing Committee]] of the National Assembly announced that [[Nguy\u1ec5n M\u1ea1nh C\u1ea7m]] had left his position as [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Vietnam)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] so as to be able to concentrate on his duties as  a deputy prime minister.{{#tag:ref|[[Nguy\u1ec5n Dy Ni\u00ean]] succeeded Nguy\u1ec5n M\u1ea1nh C\u1ea7m as foreign minister.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}}|group=note}} [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng \u0110\u00ecnh Tuy\u1ec3n]], the [[Ministry of Trade (Vietnam)|Minister of Trade]], resigned and was succeeded by [[V\u0169 Khoan]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Similar changes occurred within the party organization \u2013 for instance, [[Tr\u01b0\u01a1ng T\u1ea5n Sang]], the Secretary of the [[Ho Chi Minh City|H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh City]] Party Committee, was reassigned to head the CPV's [[Central Economic Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Economic Commission]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}} Similar changes occurred with at least seven other party officials.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=182}}\n\n===L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's downfall===\nDuring 2000, [[L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau]], the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of Vietnam|General Secretary]] of the 8th Central Committee, attempted to shore up support within the party for his reelection for a second term as general secretary.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} The 9th plenum of the 8th Central Committee (10\u201319 April) discussed draft proposals to strengthen the decision-making process at the top of the party.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} Three options were up for discussion; introducing direct elections of the [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Politburo Standing Committee]] by the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Committee]], to reestablish the [[Secretariat of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Secretariat]] (abolished at the [[8th National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam|8th National Congress]]), and the retention of the Politburo Standing Committee while at the same time reviving the Secretariat.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} After a visit to France, L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau reportedly tried to amend the [[Constitution of Vietnam|state constitution]] and the [[Statutes of the Communist Party of Vietnam|CPV statutes]] to as to allow him to serve concurrently as general secretary and [[President of Vietnam|state president]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} His stewardship as general secretary was severely tested by rural unrest, the [[Asian financial crisis]], and the continued influence of the Advisors to the Central Committee, most prominently among them being [[\u0110\u1ed7 M\u01b0\u1eddi]], L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's predecessor as general secretary.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} \u0110\u1ed7 M\u01b0\u1eddi still retained policy influence during L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's term in office, and while he was no longer a member of the [[Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Politburo]], he attended the meetings of the 8th Politburo.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} He was appointed the convenor of the 9th National Congress, a post which gave him considerable influence over congress proceedings.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}} Anyway, \u0110\u1ed7 M\u01b0\u1eddi together with [[V\u00f5 V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7t]] and [[L\u00ea \u0110\u1ee9c Anh]] sent a joint letter to the 8th Central Committee which criticized L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's leadership.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=183}}\n\nThe first session of the 11th plenum of the 8th Central Committee (held in January 2001), issued a statement which said that no one over the age of 65 could be re-elected to the Central Committee, or any other central party position.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} However, after a hard-led counter-offensive by L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau, another statement by the Central Committee was issued which stated that certain exceptions could be made by \"key cadres\".{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau pointed on a wave of demonstrations by ethnic minorities in the Central Highland in February 2001 for a reason to stay in office, so as to assure stability.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} By the end of the second session of the 11th plenum it looked to outsiders that his position was secure.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}} In a mid-April Politburo meeting, two-thirds of its members voted to retain L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau as general secretary, but on 17 April at the 12th plenum the Central Committee overturned the politburo's decision (in itself a very rare event) and voted to oust him from office.{{sfn|Abuza|2002|p=1}}\n\n===Documents===\nAt the 9th plenum of the 8th Central Committee, attended by the advisors to the Central Committee, discussed the drafting of four documents; the Political Report, the Socioeconomic Strategy for the 2001\u20132010 Period, the [[7th Five-Year Plan (Vietnam)|7th Five-Year Plan]] (2001\u20132005), and the Report on the Revision of the Party Statutes.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} [[Nguy\u1ec5n Ph\u00fa Tr\u1ecdng]], a member of the 8th Politburo and the Secretary of the [[Hanoi]] Party Committee, briefed the 9th plenum on the contentious matter that still needed to be discussed, such as sections of the Political Report and the need for further amendments to the party's statutes.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} The 10th plenum of the 8th Central Committee (26 June \u2013 4 July), according to an official communique, \"laid the ground work for the 9th National Party Congress.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} In the aftermath of the 10th plenum, the Vietnamese media gave increasing attention to internal party discussions and the then confidential political report, ''Bringing into Full Play the Strength of the Entire Nation, Continuing the Renovation Process, Accelerating Industrialization and Modernization, Building and Defending the Socialist Vietnamese Fatherland''.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} The Political Report signalled no major changes from the political report given to the 8th National Congress.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} However, there were some minor changes.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=184}} For instance, previously party documents had stated that the party and state's long term policy was \"to develop the commodity-based multi-sector economy operating in accordance with the state-managed, socialist-orientated market mechanism\", but the political report to the 9th National Congress condensed this into a single phrase, \"to develop a [[socialist-oriented market economy]].\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|pp=184\u2013185}} The political report still gave prominence to [[Ho Chi Minh Thought|H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh Thought]], the [[Socialism (Marxism)|period of transition to socialism]] (which can be shortened by \"orderly steps and big leaps forward\"), the leading role given to the state and cooperatives in the economy, and [[class struggle]].{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=185}} According to the Political Report, \"The principal content of class struggle is to successfully pursue the goal of industrialization and modernization along the lines of socialism, to struggle to frustrate all schemes and acts of sabotage by hostile forces, and to build Vietnam into a prosperous socialist country.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=185}}\n\n==Delegates==\nDuring the final quarter of 2000, and the beginning of 2001, party congresses were held at grassroots and provincial levels to elect the delegates to the 9th National Congress.{{sfn|Thayer|2001|p=185}}\n\n==The Congress and the 1st plenum==\nThe 9th National Congress met from 19\u201322 April 2001.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=82}} The elected Central Committee, the [[9th Central Committee of the Communist Party of Vietnam|9th]], was composed of 150-members (the 8th Central Committee had 170 members).{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=82}} Of these, 87 had been members of the 8th Central Committee, the rest, 63 in total, were new members.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=82}} The 9th Central Committee comprised primarily incumbent officials who held posts in either the [[Government of Vietnam|central government]] or were provincial leaders.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|pp=82\u201383}} [[L\u00ea Minh H\u01b0\u01a1ng]], a member of the [[9th Politburo of the Communist Party of Vietnam|9th Politburo]] and [[Ministry of Public Security (Vietnam)|Minister of Public Security]], led the five-member security bloc in the Central Committee, while [[L\u00ea H\u1ed3ng Anh]] was a prominent member of the bloc responsible for [[Ministry of Interior (Vietnam)|internal security]].{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} A third group, led by [[Nguy\u1ec5n V\u0103n An]], the head of the [[Central Organizing Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Organizing and Personnel Commission]], led what Carlyle Thayer referred to as the \"personnel bloc\".{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}}\n\nThe 1st plenum of the 9th Central Committee, held on 22 April, elected the 9th Politburo.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The 9th Politburo consisted of 15 members (the 8th Politburo had 19 members).{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng and [[Nguy\u1ec5n Minh Tri\u1ebft]], both considered reformers by outside observers, rose within the Politburo hierarchy, but so did L\u00ea Minh H\u01b0\u01a1ng and Nguy\u1ec5n Ph\u00fa Tr\u1ecdng, who are labelled conservatives by outside observers.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} L\u00ea H\u1ed3ng Anh, the [[Chairman of the Central Inspection Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Chairman]] of the [[Central Inspection Commission of the Communist Party of Vietnam|Central Inspection Commission]], was a newcomer to the Politburo and was ranked ninth, \"above two incumbent members\".{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} Military representation within the Politburo was reduced from four members in the 8th Politburo to one, General [[Ph\u1ea1m V\u0103n Tr\u00e0]], in the 9th Politburo.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} In contrast, military representation within the Central Committee increased overall from the 8th Central Committee, but with the majority of military members being incumbents.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}}\n\nThe Politburo Standing Committee and the Advisory Council to the Central Committee were abolished at the congress, and the Secretariat was reestablished.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The Secretariat was elected by the 1st plenum of the 9th Central Committee.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The abolishment of the Advisory Council effectively ended the behind-the-scenes influence of senior retirees.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} The congress reaffirmed Vietnam's plans of accelerating industrialization and modernization in order to become a modern-industrialized state by 2020, and adopted the 7th Five-Year Plan and the Socioeconomic Strategy for the 2001\u20132010.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=84}} According to Carlyle Thayer, these documents \"called for self-reliance, mobilization of domestic capital, the development of Vietnam's comparative advantage, and attracting external resources in the form of foreign investment capital, new technology, and managerial expertise.\"{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=84}} The Political Report stressed the need to retain good relations with fellow [[socialist state]]s and neighboring countries, while at the same time improving relations with the capitalist world.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|pp=86\u201387}}\n\nL\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau stepped down as general secretary at the 1st plenum, and was succeeded by [[N\u00f4ng \u0110\u1ee9c M\u1ea1nh]].{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=83}} [[Hu Jintao]], the [[Communist Party of China]]'s (CPC) honorary delegate to the 9th National Congress, was rumored for lobbying on L\u00ea Kh\u1ea3 Phi\u00eau's retention as general secretary on China's behalf.{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=87}} After his election to the general secretaryship, N\u00f4ng \u0110\u1ee9c M\u1ea1nh pledged to Hu Jintao that \"the relationship between Vietnam and China will develop better and better in the days to come.\" Not long after did N\u00f4ng \u0110\u1ee9c M\u1ea1nh meet personally with [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|CPC General Secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]].{{sfn|Thayer|2002|p=88}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Abuza|first=Zachary|title=The Lessons of Le Kha Phieu: Changing Rules in Vietnamese politics|pages=121\u2013145|publisher=[[Institute of Southeast Asian Studies]]|ref=CITEREFAbuza2001 |journal=[[Contemporary Southeast Asia]] |volume=24  |issue=1|date=April 2002 |url=http://www.vpa-inc.org/conference/pdf/abuza3.pdf |doi=10.1355/cs24-1h|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Thayer |first1=Carlyle |authorlink= |date=January 2001 |title=Vietnam in 2000: Toward the Ninth Party Congress |journal=[[Asian Survey]] | publisher = University of California Press |volume=41 |issue=1 |pages=181\u2013188 |doi=10.1525/as.2001.41.1.181|jstor=10.1525/as.2001.41.1.181 |ref=CITEREFThayer2001 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Thayer |first1=Carlyle |authorlink= |date=January 2002 |title=Vietnam in 2001: The Ninth Party Congress and After |journal=[[Asian Survey]] | publisher = University of California Press |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=81\u201389 |doi=10.1525/as.2002.42.1.81|ref=CITEREFThayer2002 |jstor=10.1525/as.2002.42.1.81 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{National Congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam}}\n\n[[Category:National Congresses of the Communist Party of Vietnam]]\n[[Category:2001 in Vietnam]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/9th_National_Congress_of_the_Communist_Party_of_Vietnam"}
{"title_page": "Rob Jones (footballer, born 1971)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Rob Jones\n| image          = Rob Jones.JPG\n| image_size     = 230\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Robert Marc Jones\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1971|11|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Wrexham]], Wales\n| position       = [[Right-back]]\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| years1         = 1987\u20131991\n| clubs1         = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| caps1          = 75\n| goals1         = 2\n| years2         = 1991\u20131999\n| clubs2         = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps2          = 185\n| goals2         = 0\n| years3         = 1999\n| clubs3         = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]\n| caps3          = 0\n| goals3         = 0\n| totalcaps      = 260\n| totalgoals     = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131995\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1993\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n}}\n'''Robert Marc Jones''' (born 5 November 1971) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[defender (association football)|defender]] from 1987 to 1999.\n\nAfter starting his career with [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], he went on to make a name for himself with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] before finishing his career with a brief spell with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. He was capped eight times by [[England national football team|England]].\n\n==Early life==\nJones, who grew up in [[Ellesmere Port]], Cheshire, is the grandson of former Liverpool player [[Bill Jones (footballer born 1921)|Bill Jones]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Crewe Alexandra (1987\u20131991)===\nJones began his career with [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], signing professional forms at the age of 17 on 20 December 1988 when Crewe were in [[Football League Division Four|Division Four]]. The right-back settled quickly, quietly going about his defensive duties until being spotted during the [[1991-92 in English football|1991\u201392]] season, accidentally, by Liverpool manager [[Graeme Souness]] who was at [[Gresty Road]] looking at a different player. Souness put in an offer of \u00a3300,000 which was accepted, and on 4 October 1991, a month before his 20th birthday, he became a Liverpool player.\n\n===Liverpool (1991\u20131999)===\nHis debut for the Reds came on 6 October 1991, just 48 hours after he had signed on at [[Anfield]], with a game at [[Old Trafford]], where he excelled against United winger [[Ryan Giggs]] and was named Man Of The Match in a goalless league draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sporting Spotlight : Rob Jones|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20554929|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> By the end of the season, Jones had won over the coach, become a regular in the starting line-up, had gained his first international cap, as well as helped the Reds to the final of the [[FA Cup]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] \u2013 a final that saw Liverpool beat [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] 2\u20130. However, he was ruled out of England's [[UEFA Euro 1992|Euro 92]] squad due to shin splints.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/CmpEC/CmpEC1992Squad.html|title=England in the European Championship - 1992 Squad Records|first=Peter|last=Young|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOver the next four seasons he was a regular member of the Liverpool starting line-up and in the sides that beat [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] 2\u20131 in the 1995 [[Football League Cup]] final and lost 1\u20130 to Man United in the [[1996 FA Cup Final]].\n\nWhen Liverpool signed midfielder [[Jason McAteer]], who arrived in [[1995-96 in English football|1995]], [[Roy Evans]] converted McAteer to right-back and employed Jones on the left-side in a [[Defender (association football)#Wingback|wingback]] role as Liverpool changed from their normal [[Formation (association football)|4\u20134\u20132]] to an attack-minded [[Formation (association football)|5\u20133\u20132]] formation.\n\nAfter the [[1996 FA Cup Final]], Jones was advised to take a six-month break from football due to back problems. He returned to action, but the next two seasons were plagued by injuries, and in April [[1997-98 in English football|1998]] he played what was to be his last game for Liverpool against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{Soccerbase season|3995|1997|name=Rob Jones|accessdate=2019-10-23}}</ref> An injury in his left knee could not be fixed, despite three operations, and at the end of the [[1998-99 in English football|1998\u201399]] season, in which he had not played a game, he was released on a free transfer by new coach that year, [[Gerard Houllier]], who was ushering in a new era at the club to eliminate the club's [[Spice Boys (footballers)|Spice Boys]] public image and stereotype.\n\n===West Ham United (1999)===\nJones joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], on non-contract terms, on 17 July 1999. He was named in the side that began the [[1999 UEFA Intertoto Cup|Intertoto Cup]] third round second leg tie against [[FC Jokerit]], but was substituted after the first half as a result of aggravating his knee injury. This proved to be his last senior appearance, as he retired in August 1999.\n\n==International career==\nAt international level Jones was eligible to play for [[Wales national football team|Wales]], as he was born in Wrexham, but it was [[Graham Taylor (football manager)|Graham Taylor]] who selected him and gave him his international debut for [[England national football team|England]] in the 2\u20130 win over [[France national football team|France]] at Wembley on 19 February 1992 \u2013 just four months after he had made the move from Fourth Division football to the First Division. Injury forced Jones to miss the [[Euro 92|1992 European Championships]] where he would have been the first choice right-back, but he went on to win eight international caps over the next few years.\n\n==Style of play==\nJones had played 243 times for the Reds, earned several accolades and man of the match awards, although he famously never scored a goal for Liverpool. Teammates [[Steve McManaman]] described him to [[FourFourTwo]] magazine as the best defender he ever played with, naming him in his all time perfect XI alongside the likes of [[Zinedine Zidane]], [[Luis Figo]], and [[Roberto Carlos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/steve-mcmanaman-perfect-xi|title=Steve McManaman: Perfect XI|date=1 March 2011|publisher=}}</ref> Younger teammate [[Jamie Carragher]] also once said of Jones: \"I played with Rob Jones a few times and he was a bit unfortunate with injuries and his best form was probably before I got into the team, when he was as good as probably anything in Europe at the time ... He was playing out of his skin and I think if he'd have stayed fit he probably would have gone on to win 70 or 80 caps for England instead of [[Gary Neville]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/Profile/340|title=Liverpool career stats for Rob Jones - LFChistory - Stats galore for Liverpool FC!|first=|last=LFChistory.net|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAfter failing to get over a knee injury that had severely affected him since late 1996, Jones announced his retirement on 28 August 1999, aged just 27.\n\n==Retirement==\nSince his retirement, Jones and his wife have built-up Kids Academy, a [[Franchising|franchise]]-based business of children's nurseries across the UK, but now called Evolution Childcare which also now extends into the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Austin|first=Simon|title=Sporting Spotlight: Rob Jones|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20554929|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=LivEcho3326660/> On 3 September 2014 Rob and his wife were seen in Abu Dhabi promoting the nursery opened at Abu Dhabi airport by Etihad.\n\nIn October 2013 it was announced that Jones would be taking up a coaching role with [[Liverpool F.C. Academy]],<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2441327/Robbie-Fowler-Steve-McManaman-Rob-Jones-return-Liverpool-youth-academy-mentors.html|title= Liverpool legends Fowler, McManaman and Jones return to club to help Kop kids|date=2 October 2013|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref> where his eldest son Declan is a trainee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-fc-greats-robbie-fowler-6123557|title=Reds greats return to the fold to help next generation of players|first=James|last=Pearce|date=2 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJones lives in [[Warrington]], with his wife Sue and their three children.<ref name=LivEcho3326660>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-liverpool-fc-player-rob-3326660|title=Former Liverpool FC player Rob Jones rekindles his affection for Reds after injury cruelly ended his career|first=James|last=Pearce|date=5 December 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he released his autobiography, titled ''Robbed''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hunter|first=Steve|title=Great new book for LFC fans|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/great-new-book-for-lfc-fans|publisher=Liverpool F.C.|accessdate=16 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119065929/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/great-new-book-for-lfc-fans|archivedate=19 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career honours==\n\n===Crewe Alexandra===\n'''Third Place''' (Promotion)\n* 1988\u20131989 [[Football League Fourth Division]] (Level 4)\n\n=== Liverpool===\n'''Winner'''\n* 1991\u201392 [[FA Cup]]\n* 1994\u201395 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of England international footballers born outside England]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lfchistory.net/player_profile.asp?player_id=340 Profile] at [http://www.lfchistory.net LFCHistory.net]\n*[http://www.thisisanfield.com/columnists/2007/09/rob-jones-the-best-we-never-had/ Thisisanfield.com Forgotten Heroes]\n* [http://sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/searchresults.asp?ButtonLeap=0&countryLinkDescription=+matching+search+results&FootballHeroName=rob+jones&FootballHeroClubCountry=&FootballHeroDecade=Select+One&SearchButton=Search Rob Jones index at Sporting-heroes.net]\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n{{1991\u201392 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{1994\u201395 Premier League Team of the Year}}\n{{100 players who shook the Kop}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Rob}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Wrexham]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Crewe Alexandra F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:People from Ellesmere Port]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Rob Jones\n| image          = Rob Jones.JPG\n| image_size     = 230\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Robert Marc Jones\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1971|11|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Wrexham]], Wales\n| position       = [[Right-back]]\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = \n| years1         = 1987\u20131991\n| clubs1         = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]\n| caps1          = 75\n| goals1         = 2\n| years2         = 1991\u20131999\n| clubs2         = [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| caps2          = 185\n| goals2         = 0\n| years3         = 1999\n| clubs3         = [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]\n| caps3          = 0\n| goals3         = 0\n| totalcaps      = 260\n| totalgoals     = 2\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131995\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1993\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n}}\n'''Robert Marc Jones''' (born 5 November 1971) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[defender (association football)|defender]] from 1987 to 1999.\n\nAfter starting his career with [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], he went on to make a name for himself with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] before finishing his career with a brief spell with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. He was capped eight times by [[England national football team|England]].\n\n==Early life==\nJones, who grew up in [[Ellesmere Port]], Cheshire, is the grandson of former Liverpool player [[Bill Jones (footballer born 1921)|Bill Jones]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Crewe Alexandra (1987\u20131991)===\nJones began his career with [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], signing professional forms at the age of 17 on 20 December 1988 when Crewe were in [[Football League Division Four|Division Four]]. The right-back settled quickly, quietly going about his defensive duties until being spotted during the [[1991-92 in English football|1991\u201392]] season, accidentally, by Liverpool manager [[Graeme Souness]] who was at [[Gresty Road]] looking at a different player. Souness put in an offer of \u00a3300,000 which was accepted, and on 4 October 1991, a month before his 20th birthday, he became a Liverpool player.\n\n===Liverpool (1991\u20131999)===\nHis debut for the Reds came on 6 October 1991, just 48 hours after he had signed on at [[Anfield]], with a game at [[Old Trafford]], where he excelled against United winger [[Ryan Giggs]] and was named Man Of The Match in a goalless league draw.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sporting Spotlight : Rob Jones|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20554929|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> By the end of the season, Jones had won over the coach, become a regular in the starting line-up, had gained his first international cap, as well as helped the Reds to the final of the [[FA Cup]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]] \u2013 a final that saw Liverpool beat [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] 2\u20130. However, he was ruled out of England's [[UEFA Euro 1992|Euro 92]] squad due to shin splints.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/CmpEC/CmpEC1992Squad.html|title=England in the European Championship - 1992 Squad Records|first=Peter|last=Young|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOver the next four seasons he was a regular member of the Liverpool starting line-up and in the sides that beat [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] 2\u20131 in the 1995 [[Football League Cup]] final and lost 1\u20130 to Man United in the [[1996 FA Cup Final]].\n\nWhen Liverpool signed midfielder [[Jason McAteer]], who arrived in [[1995-96 in English football|1995]], [[Roy Evans]] converted McAteer to right-back and employed Jones on the left-side in a [[Defender (association football)#Wingback|wingback]] role as Liverpool changed from their normal [[Formation (association football)|4\u20134\u20132]] to an attack-minded [[Formation (association football)|5\u20133\u20132]] formation.\n\nAfter the [[1996 FA Cup Final]], Jones was advised to take a six-month break from football due to back problems. He returned to action, but the next two seasons were plagued by injuries, and in April [[1997-98 in English football|1998]] he played what was to be his last game for Liverpool against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{Soccerbase season|3995|1997|name=Rob Jones|accessdate=2019-10-23}}</ref> An injury in his left knee could not be fixed, despite three operations, and at the end of the [[1998-99 in English football|1998\u201399]] season, in which he had not played a game, he was released on a free transfer by new coach that year, [[Gerard Houllier]], who was ushering in a new era at the club to eliminate the club's [[Spice Boys (footballers)|Spice Boys]] public image and stereotype.\n\n===West Ham United (1999)===\nHe joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], on non-contract terms, on 17 July 1999, and featured for them in a single [[Intertoto Cup]] game and featured in his second and what would be his final professional career match for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] which lasted 45 minutes as a result of re-aggravating his knee, he retired shortly after this, having played his last senior game at the age of 27.\n\n==International career==\nAt international level Jones was eligible to play for [[Wales national football team|Wales]], as he was born in Wrexham, but it was [[Graham Taylor (football manager)|Graham Taylor]] who selected him and gave him his international debut for [[England national football team|England]] in the 2\u20130 win over [[France national football team|France]] at Wembley on 19 February 1992 \u2013 just four months after he had made the move from Fourth Division football to the First Division. Injury forced Jones to miss the [[Euro 92|1992 European Championships]] where he would have been the first choice right-back, but he went on to win eight international caps over the next few years.\n\n==Style of play==\nJones had played 243 times for the Reds, earned several accolades and man of the match awards, although he famously never scored a goal for Liverpool. Teammates [[Steve McManaman]] described him to [[FourFourTwo]] magazine as the best defender he ever played with, naming him in his all time perfect XI alongside the likes of [[Zinedine Zidane]], [[Luis Figo]], and [[Roberto Carlos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/steve-mcmanaman-perfect-xi|title=Steve McManaman: Perfect XI|date=1 March 2011|publisher=}}</ref> Younger teammate [[Jamie Carragher]] also once said of Jones: \"I played with Rob Jones a few times and he was a bit unfortunate with injuries and his best form was probably before I got into the team, when he was as good as probably anything in Europe at the time ... He was playing out of his skin and I think if he'd have stayed fit he probably would have gone on to win 70 or 80 caps for England instead of [[Gary Neville]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfchistory.net/Players/Player/Profile/340|title=Liverpool career stats for Rob Jones - LFChistory - Stats galore for Liverpool FC!|first=|last=LFChistory.net|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAfter failing to get over a knee injury that had severely affected him since late 1996, Jones announced his retirement on 28 August 1999, aged just 27.\n\n==Retirement==\nSince his retirement, Jones and his wife have built-up Kids Academy, a [[Franchising|franchise]]-based business of children's nurseries across the UK, but now called Evolution Childcare which also now extends into the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Austin|first=Simon|title=Sporting Spotlight: Rob Jones|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20554929|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=LivEcho3326660/> On 3 September 2014 Rob and his wife were seen in Abu Dhabi promoting the nursery opened at Abu Dhabi airport by Etihad.\n\nIn October 2013 it was announced that Jones would be taking up a coaching role with [[Liverpool F.C. Academy]],<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2441327/Robbie-Fowler-Steve-McManaman-Rob-Jones-return-Liverpool-youth-academy-mentors.html|title= Liverpool legends Fowler, McManaman and Jones return to club to help Kop kids|date=2 October 2013|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref> where his eldest son Declan is a trainee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-fc-greats-robbie-fowler-6123557|title=Reds greats return to the fold to help next generation of players|first=James|last=Pearce|date=2 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJones lives in [[Warrington]], with his wife Sue and their three children.<ref name=LivEcho3326660>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-liverpool-fc-player-rob-3326660|title=Former Liverpool FC player Rob Jones rekindles his affection for Reds after injury cruelly ended his career|first=James|last=Pearce|date=5 December 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he released his autobiography, titled ''Robbed''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hunter|first=Steve|title=Great new book for LFC fans|url=http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/great-new-book-for-lfc-fans|publisher=Liverpool F.C.|accessdate=16 November 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119065929/http://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/latest-news/great-new-book-for-lfc-fans|archivedate=19 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career honours==\n\n===Crewe Alexandra===\n'''Third Place''' (Promotion)\n* 1988\u20131989 [[Football League Fourth Division]] (Level 4)\n\n=== Liverpool===\n'''Winner'''\n* 1991\u201392 [[FA Cup]]\n* 1994\u201395 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of England international footballers born outside England]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lfchistory.net/player_profile.asp?player_id=340 Profile] at [http://www.lfchistory.net LFCHistory.net]\n*[http://www.thisisanfield.com/columnists/2007/09/rob-jones-the-best-we-never-had/ Thisisanfield.com Forgotten Heroes]\n* [http://sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/searchresults.asp?ButtonLeap=0&countryLinkDescription=+matching+search+results&FootballHeroName=rob+jones&FootballHeroClubCountry=&FootballHeroDecade=Select+One&SearchButton=Search Rob Jones index at Sporting-heroes.net]\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n{{1991\u201392 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{1994\u201395 Premier League Team of the Year}}\n{{100 players who shook the Kop}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Rob}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Wrexham]]\n[[Category:Association football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:Crewe Alexandra F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Liverpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:English people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:People from Ellesmere Port]]\n", "name_user": "Hammersfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWest Ham United (1999)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rob_Jones_(footballer,_born_1971)"}
